<HEAD>U.S. Style Marriage and Divorce Criticized by Americans, Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese attitudes toward marriage, divorce and the family are changing but the American model is an unattractive one, young adults from both countries said at a cultural exchange. Thirty university students from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and 30 from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, ranging in age from 17 to 25, compared cultural and social traditions at a gathering that produced strong criticism from both sides of the high <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> divorce rate. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1985 had five divorces and 10.2 marriages per 1,000 people. Comparable Japanese figures were 1.39 divorces and 6.2 marriages per 1,000. `` Americans seem so crazy about kids, but when they divorce are n't they forgetting about the children?'' said <PERSON> Tadakatsu </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsuruno </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> at the daylong session last week in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> co-sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Nihon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Keizai </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese economic newspaper, and <ORGANIZATION> Konica </ORGANIZATION>, the photographic and electronics company. The Japanese, from 11 universities, were winners of an essay contest on the two countries' roles in the world. The Americans were engaged in Japanese or other foreign studies at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> universities. University of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> student <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> said the high <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> divorce rate `` is a sign of how individualism has gone out of control'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He called it `` individualism with no altruism.'' But despite their criticism of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trends, Tsuruno and other Japanese said things also are changing at home. `` The Japanese attitude to marriage is approaching the American way ... with people thinking more for themselves,'' Tsuruno noted. `` We still have arranged marriages, but 99 percent of my generation will find wives by themselves.'' <PERSON> Noriko </PERSON> <PERSON> Takahashi </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> medical student, said she will make the final decision on her future husband although she will consult with her parents. She said that if someone simply wants romance, `` you can have it without marriage. But the reason for marriage is to have children and propagate generation after generation'' of the family. <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Pochop </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s divorce rate is likely to rise as Japanese women acquire the ability to support themselves. Without it, she said, many Japanese wives are forced to accept their husbands' liaisons with other women, `` a situation <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women would find intolerable.'' A moderator, Prof. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s divorce rate is rising, with more older women divorcing after raising their children to adulthood.
