 The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> must consider the needs of the homeless before the agency auctions off government-owned, foreclosed homes to the highest bidder, a federal judge says. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> temporarily barred <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday from selling 170 single-family homes in the metropolitan <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> area. The sale was scheduled for today. Last week, another federal judge in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> blocked <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> from selling 200 foreclosed homes in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. The actions are part of a broader effort to force the federal government to make some of <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s inventory of 47,000 foreclosed houses available to the homeless. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, in issuing his temporary restraining order, said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> had violated federal laws by refusing to make a survey of its stock of buildings and properties and determine which might be transferred to non-profit groups that provide services for the homeless. He also said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has not complied with the law which calls for `` the realization as soon as feasible of the goal of a decent home and a suitable living environment for every American family.'' `` <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> can not just sell to the highest bidder,'' he said. `` The government can not not just consider the amount of revenue coming in.'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said his temporary restraining order would last until Sept. 14 while Judge <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON>, who has jurisdiction over the case, schedules further action. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> is acquiring foreclosed properties at a rate of about 7,000 each month. Because it has been selling between 6,000 and 7,000 of the properties monthly, the agency has accumulated a `` rolling inventory'' of about 47,000 homes, the largest backlog in its history. The surge in <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s stock of properties reflects a rash of foreclosures on properties in the oil-producing states, and an increase in the overall volume of homes insured by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> in the wake of lower interest rates two years ago.
