<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Prices up in August but Trend Moderating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farm commodity prices as a group were still going up last month, although a new <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report shows that some major items were starting to level off in August. The department's overall price index rose 2.1 percent from July, averaging 13 percent more than in August 1987. Also, the new figures released on Tuesday showed that the index rose only 2.9 percent in July instead of the preliminary reading of 3.6 percent announced a month ago. Since April, as drought cut into this year's harvest prospects, farm commodity prices overall have climbed 10.8 percent. However, there were some indications in the August report that the upward spiral began to weaken. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said in its preliminary report that higher prices for cattle, apples, tomatoes and lettuce contributed most to the August increase, while prices declined for cotton, corn, onions and soybeans. In the earlier months, corn and soybeans helped lead the way for rising prices. However, by late July, widespread rains began to dampen further increases, although the drought of 1988 has not been broken by any means. At the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday grain and soybean futures closed sharply higher, but it was on the strength of new export business, not further crop losses due to drought, analysts said. Moreover, they said, the corn and soybean crops have passed their most critical stages of development. Based on Aug. 1 estimates, this year's corn harvest may drop 37 percent from 1987; wheat, 13 percent; and soybeans 23 percent. `` All feed grain and soybean prices declined from July, but rough -LRB- unmilled -RRB- rice and all wheat prices increased slightly,'' the report said. `` Average prices of beef cattle and calves increased sharply from July but were below the high levels recorded during February through May of this year.'' Prices of some major commodities are based on mid-month averages and then are revised the following month when additional information is available. As a commodity group, prices of feed grains and hay dropped 2.8 percent from July to August, but still averaged 68 percent above a year ago, the report said. Prices of meat animals rose 4.3 percent as a group but averaged 0.6 percent below the year-earlier mark. Beef cattle prices averaged $ 66.40 per 100 pounds of liveweight, up $ 3.20 from July. Hog prices increased $ 1 from July to $ 46.80 in August. Apple prices at the farm level, rose to 26.1 cents per pound in August from 19.7 cents in July and 16 cents a year ago. Lettuce was reported at $ 12.20 per 100 pounds, up from $ 7.62 in July but far below the $ 18 of last year. Tomatoes, at $ 41.70 per 100 pounds, were up from $ 31 in July and $ 17.30 in August 1987. Overall, the August all-crops price index was up 2.3 percent from July, averaging 33 percent above the year-ago level. The August price index for all livestock and livestock products was up 3.4 percent from July and averaged 1.3 percent more than a year earlier. Higher prices for cattle, hogs, milk, turkeys and eggs accounted for the increase from July. Consumer food prices are expected to rise 3 percent to 5 percent this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987. Before the drought took hold, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> was predicting a 1988 food price hike of 2 percent to 4 percent. Department officials have predicted that the drought may add 2 percentage points to food prices in 1989, above the expected increase in inflation, currently forecast at around 4 percent. That could mean a 1989 food price increase in the range of 6 percent to 7 percent. Tuesday's report said: _ Cattle averaged $ 66.40 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally, up from $ 63.20 in July and $ 61.90 reported for August 1987 Those are averages for all types of cattle sold as beef. _ Hogs averaged $ 45.40 per 100 pounds, compared with $ 44.10 in July and $ 58.60 a year earlier _ Corn, at $ 2.66 a bushel, was down from $ 2.72 in July and the average of $ 1.47 per bushel a year earlier _ Wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures, averaged $ 3.56 per bushel, compared with $ 3.50 in July and $ 2.36 a year earlier _ Rice averaged $ 7.61 per 100 pounds, compared with $ 7.51 in July and $ 3.74 a year earlier _ Soybeans were $ 8.40 per bushel, compared with $ 8.50 in July and $ 5.02 a year earlier _ Upland cotton was reported at 55.2 cents per pound, compared with 58.6 in July and 63.7 cents in August 1987 _ Eggs were 59.9 cents per dozen, compared with 62.2 cents in July and 51.9 cents a year earlier _ Milk was $ 11.60 per 100 pounds, compared with $ 11.40 in July and $ 12.20 a year earlier _ Broilers were 41.9 cents per pound, live weight, compared with 42.1 cents in July and 31.7 cents a year ago
