<HEAD>Officials Claim Success in Drug Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities say a 30-nation narcotics crackdown resulted in more than 1,200 arrests in the past month and should lead to further drug busts in this hemisphere. `` Some operations are still going on,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutensohn </PERSON>, head of cocaine investigations at the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. Attorney General <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> and a host of other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and foreign officials said Tuesday that 30 countries had participated in a series of anti-drug trafficking operations this month, primarily in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said authorities seized 11 tons of cocaine and destroyed 244 tons of marijuana, 118,000 coca plants and 13 cocaine laboratories. Authorities also demolished seven hidden airstrips and seized $ 3.8 million in cash, he said. While <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the effort did not represent victory in the war against drugs, he said the `` cooperative nature'' of the operations represented a new avenue in stamping out trafficking. `` Heretofore, each of the nations of the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> has been pursuing the war on drugs in a more or less unilateral or bilateral fashion,'' he said. The participating countries, all members of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, shared resources and intelligence and, in a few cases, staged cross-border operations. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> did not orchestrate the drug busts, though it did serve as a clearinghouse for data. Instead, each country planned and executed its drug operations, often in concert with other countries. `` By doing it all over at once, you disrupt the operation,'' <PERSON> Gutensohn </PERSON> said. Since many drug traffickers ignore national boundaries, it is vital to close in on traffickers on many fronts, he said. In <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, for instance, military authorities seized cocaine laboratories in the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huallaga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> that are used by members of the powerful <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Calli </PERSON> drug cartels, based in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. Cocaine labs also were seized in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> itself, as well as <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>. Among some other actions cited by the officials: _ About 100 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardsmen </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> helped border patrol officials inspect vehicles that crossed into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ As a result of information developed abroad, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> officials seized two tons of cocaine and about $ 2 million in cash _ Military officers from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> operated along the joint border _ Officials in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> worked together to seize chemicals used for cocaine at points along the border <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> participated in the operation as a member of the conference, but did not receive any `` centralized intelligence'' from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s military dictator, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, has been indicted by two federal grand juries in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has sought his ouster since early this year, applying economic sanctions that have hurt <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s economy. _ European nations and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> stepped up monitoring of vessels, cargo and aircraft arriving from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>
