<FIRST>r w PM-NixonTapes Bjt   08-31 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nixon Tapes, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nixon Was Reluctant To Tape White House Sessions, Former Aide Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s former top aide says the 37th president not only was reluctant to install an extensive taping system in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but that he quickly lost awareness that his every conversation was being recorded. `` The historiography of the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration will eventually be much the richer as a result of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s decision to tape-record his meetings and telephone conversations,'' writes H.R. <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s onetime chief of staff. `` <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> was not thinking of historians when he made this decision, but they will be the ultimate beneficiaries.'' <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> discusses the origin of the taping system, which provided the evidence that eventually drove <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> from office in the Watergate scandal, in the summer issue of Prologue, the quarterly publication of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON>'s latest account is much softer in tone and less critical of <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> than when he described the same events in a 1978 book, `` The Ends of Power.'' `` It is amazing to me when I think back to the first days, weeks and months of the taping system's existence how quickly I forgot about it,'' <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> writes. `` For a short time, I worried that it might not be working, and I dispatched someone to test the machinery. But the worry quickly passed, as did any awareness at all that <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s conversations _ my conversations, often _ were being taped. I think <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> lost his awareness of the system even more quickly than I did.'' That dovetails with <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s own memory that `` initially I was conscious of the taping, but before long I accepted it as part of the surroundings.'' <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> says his book 10 years ago focused on the Watergate scandal that drove <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> from office in 1974 and that, `` It was unfortunately sensational in many instances where I would have preferred it to be more reasoned and thorough.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> fired <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> in April 1973 at the height of the coverup of the break-in at <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in the Watergate complex in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> served an 18-month prison term for his part in the affair. In the book he said <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> had `` fudged'' the tape story in various ways, `` climaxing with the assertion on television in 1977 that he had ordered me to destroy all of the tapes.'' There is no reference to that in the Prologue article. The former aide said he chose to write about the taping system because the archives next year will release 60 hours of the recordings for public listening. `` <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> abhorred the idea of taping the president's meetings and telephone conversations,'' <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> writes. He said he and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> discovered the taping system of his predecessor, <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, on inauguration day and that the new president ordered it removed. The major reason for the system, <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> says now as before, was <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s failed attempt to halt inaccurate reports that came out of his meetings with various people. Other reasons, he said, were that <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> wanted records for his memoirs and an accurate account of what foreign leaders said to him. `` Something had to be done, both <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and I agreed, to ensure that we possessed an accurate record of what was said in meetings,'' <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> writes. They had tried using note-takers but quit because they inhibited conversations, and they had tried debriefing visitors as they left the Oval Office. In late 1970 or early 1971, <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> recalls, word got to <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> that <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> felt he was foolish for not keeping a record of what was going on and that such a record was necessary for memoirs. `` <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> suddenly was receptive to the idea of taping his meetings,'' <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> says. `` Finally, still reluctantly, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> agreed that taping was the best way.''
