<HEAD>Boos Follow Quayle On Campaign Trail, But They're For the Press</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There are plenty of boos on the campaign trail with <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, but they're not for the candidate They're for the press entourage traveling with him. The press is generally seen by pro-Quayle audiences as the skunk at the picnic as he makes his way around the country, because of reporters' questions about the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, his academic record, his resume and various other personal details <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has called `` side events.'' `` Let him alone!'' the audience shouts as reporters try to waylay the vice presidential nominee. Some of the shouts are less polite. Signs like `` Media Beware,'' `` Cut <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON>'s Tongue Out'' and `` Press Go Home'' greet the traveling press. Last week, on <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s seven-state trip, at almost every stop were identical signs with the word `` Press'' encircled in red and with a red slash mark through the word, leading some to suspect an organized effort. At a stop in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, one unidentified teen-ager held such a sign and told reporters, `` Someone gave it to me when I came in the door and I liked it.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Prosperi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s spokesman, said he had no idea where the signs came from. `` I'm quite confident that it is nobody affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> Bush-Quayle </ORGANIZATION> organization in any way, shape or form,'' he said. `` That's just not the way we do business.'' <PERSON> Prosperi </PERSON> said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> does not intend to `` have a fight with the press.'' `` We're here to have a fight with the other guys on the issues,'' he said. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was asked Sunday as he flew home whether he felt at times as if he were running against the news media, instead of the Democrats. `` I'm running with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' he replied. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> wo n't say whether he thinks the press is out to get him, telling reporters `` only you can answer that question.'' But he says he does not disagree with his wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, who last week said she felt the press was biased against <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> because he was a conservative. But <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has made it clear he dislikes the intensive media scrutiny that has followed him since he became <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate and allegations surfaced that he pulled strings to get into the National Guard during the Vietnam War and into law school after an average performance in college. At the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> State Fair in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> petted a <LOCATION> Labrador </LOCATION> retriever guide dog and when the dog just lay there with his eyes rolled up, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, `` Now I know how it feels to be hounded.'' He tends to make sarcastic references to the press in his stump speech, often referring to `` my newfound friends in the news media'' or `` my cheering section.'' The references are not lost on the audiences. At one appearance in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, reporters who tried to ask <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> about the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> issue as he made his way shaking hands were dealt with roughly. A large woman hit one female reporter's arm and shoulder and turned and dealt another one a hefty body block. She said the two women were endangering a group of Scouts. `` I'm just trying to protect the children,'' she shouted. The hostility reached its peak at a rally in <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s hometown of <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, as he and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaigned together on their first day after the Republican convention. At a news conference that was piped to the crowd over the public address system, the crowd cheered <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s answers and booed reporters' questions. `` B-o-r-i-n-g,'' they shouted. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> could n't resist another reference to the press, when he spoke to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION>. `` I feel that I am very accustomed to fighting fires these last couple of weeks.'' When he was presented with a fire chief's hat, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said: `` This is going to be prominently displayed on my airplane ... right in front of where the press is sitting.'' The hat will join another memento. At a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> stop last week, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s aides quickly grabbed up a bumper sticker which stated: `` I Do n't Love the Liberal Media.'' It is affixed it to the cabin door that faces the press section of the aircraft.
