10th graf pvs, `On Tuesday ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> left for <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> on Wednesday for his first talks with Polish authorities since Solidarity was banned. The government hoped the meeting would end two weeks of labor unrest. Asked what he would discuss with Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> during the talks, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said: `` How to make up for the past seven years.'' Solidarity was crushed in a 1981 military crackdown. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> traveled by car with senior Solidarity adviser <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>. The meeting <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s advisers said would be held Wednesday would follow four days of maneuvering started by <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>'s proposal on Friday that officials and worker representatives hold `` round-table'' discussions. A communique from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling Politburo, distributed by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION>, mentioned a round-table meeting, endorsed it and said <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> should `` carry on with the mission entrusted to him.'' It was not clear, however, whether the reference was to the Wednesday meeting or the minister's original proposal on Friday. No other official reference was made to Walesa-Kiszczak talks. Ten enterprises in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> remained on strike. At its height, the current labor trouble involved 20 sites employing 100,000 people and was the worst since 1980. Solidarity spokesmen said there was no agreement for an immediate end to the strikes, in which a central demand has been making Solidarity legal again. <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> called the decision for talks `` a historic moment.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> last met with the government on behalf of the union in late 1981. On Tuesday evening, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> left the strikebound <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> shipyard, where he works as an electrician, to confer with advisers and Bishop <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Goclowski </PERSON> at nearby <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brygida </LOCATION>'s church. He emerged from the rectory with the bishop later to cheers and chants from supporters. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said earlier in the day that talks could begin as soon as <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> called off the strike at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> shipyard, where the Soviet bloc's first free union was born in the labor uprising of 1980, but aide <PERSON> Piotr </PERSON> <PERSON> Konopka </PERSON> said: `` For the present, the strike is still on.'' He said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> would attend the Wednesday meeting as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Self-Governing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION>, the labor federation's full name. While the government expressed its willingness to talk, strikers at the <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> steel mill in southeastern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> said soldiers had moved into the town and helicopters flew over the plant. Workers are occupying the shipyard and steel mill, as is customary during strikes in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. In a reference to the <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> strike, <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>'s ministry and the armed forces general staff issued a statement saying: `` In case of the continuation of the illegal strike action, appropriate lawful measures will be taken.'' <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Michnik </PERSON>, a historian and senior <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> adviser, said Tuesday night: `` The talks begin exactly on the anniversary of the August agreements'' that created Solidarity as a legal union in 1980. `` We want to believe that a new chance begins and it will be at a time when Poles can make use of this chance,'' he said. `` The results of this meeting tomorrow will be very important for the fate of the country and the world.'' <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> said: `` We hope that this meeting will serve the purpose of dialogue and agreement and the most important issue, which is trade union pluralism and the legalization of Solidarity.'' Urban told his weekly news conference Tuesday: `` The stoppage of strikes by Mr. <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and the shipyard where he works would mean automatically convening a round table.'' He said no rules had been made for the agenda of the `` round-table'' talks with representatives of various segments of society, to be moderated by <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, who suggested them last Friday. `` We are ready for talks ... with all those who respect the law, a significant symptom of which is avoiding participation in illegal srikes and moreover contributing to their stoppage,'' Urban said. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> had said he would not call off the <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> shipyard strike unless Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s government promised to include trade union pluralism in the discussion and he was allowed to take part as the recognized leader of Solidarity. He traditionally marks the Aug. 31 date of the signing of the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> agreements by laying a wreath at a monument to workers killed in labor unrest during 1970. It is near the Lenin shipyard's main gate <PERSON> Michnik </PERSON> said earlier that Urban's statement represented only a `` preliminary step'' because it `` does not say exactly what can be understood by the term round table, who would sit at it, and the subject of the talks.'' Most strikers have demanded higher pay and better working conditions in addition to legalization of Solidarity, but the status of the outlawed union is the only demand at <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Piotr </PERSON> <PERSON> Niemczyk </PERSON>, a Solidarity spokesman in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, said the workers had authoritized <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> to negotiate for them.
