<HEAD>California Governor Squashes Proposed State Mollusk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When it comes to representing <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the banana slug just wo n't do, Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> said in vetoing a bill that designated the slimy, slothful creature the state's official mollusk. The veto by the image-conscious governor, announced Tuesday, squashed the hopes of a group of <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Birds </ORGANIZATION> and Camp Fire girls from the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area who led the campaign to make the banana slug a state mascot. `` I feel really bad that he vetoed it,'' says <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Moses </PERSON>, 9, whose Blue Bird troop worked six weeks lobbying. `` I mean, why did he have to do that? He did n't know anything about it. I hope he watched the news about it.'' <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> said he vetoed the bill because the large, brilliant yellow mollusk, which can eat poison oak without getting a rash, is n't a true Californian. `` If there is a need to designate a state mollusk, it would be more appropriate to select one that is indigenous to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and perhaps one that is more representative of the international reputation that <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> enjoys,'' he said in his veto message. The governor added that the dubious honor of being the banana slug's home state may belong to wetter neighbors to the north, since the species was first identified near the mouth of the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and lives as far north as <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. But members of the <ORGANIZATION> Redwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Birds </ORGANIZATION> and the office of the legislator who carried their slug bill said the governor is misinformed about the banana slug, which has the scientific name Ariolimax columbianus and lives in damp coastal forest areas throughout the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopcraft </PERSON>, an aide to Democratic Assemblyman <PERSON> Bryon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>, said four of five kinds of banana slugs are native to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` I think basically the banana slug has gotten a bad rap,'' said <PERSON> Hopcraft </PERSON>, who wore a yellow armband Tuesday in memory of <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>'s bill `` They're obviously easy to look down upon and they do have some odd habits. Perhaps, the governor looked too much at that and not their good side. `` As far as its representative qualities, it's absolutely a unique example of the diversity of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s wildlife.'' <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>, a Republican who's made a personal campaign of promoting <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> trade nationally and overseas, suggested the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> may not need an official slug at all. And if <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> must have a mollusk, he'd prefer the pismo clam, black abalone, red abalone, turban shell, two-spotted octupus, common squid or another breed of mussel unique to the state. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has several official mascots, including a tree, a fossil, a reptile, a fish, a rock and even a state insect in addition to the usual bird, animal and flower. The Legislature sent a bill to the governor Monday that would designate the square dance as the official folk dance, and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> swing, or jitterbug, as the official dance. <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> has not acted on that measure. The banana slug gained notoriety a few years ago when students at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> chose it as the official school mascot over the sea lion, despite the objections of the university's president.
