<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To firefighters on the front lines, breathing the smoke is like going through four packs of cigarettes a day, but for those elsewhere in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, it poses little danger, doctors say. `` I think the main thing is it's much more an irritant,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, who works at the Old Faithful medical clinic in the nation's oldest national park. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pardee </PERSON>, a retiree from <LOCATION> Casa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, who spends summers working in a general store at Old Faithful, can attest to the irritation. `` Whenever we get these inversions, we'd get all choked up,'' <PERSON> Pardee </PERSON> said Monday when he came to the clinic seeking relief. `` The last few days, it's been really bad. `` We like to walk back and forth to work,'' he continued. `` It's about three-quarters of a mile, but it's gotten so bad that by the time we got to work we could hardly talk to anybody. <PERSON> Pardee </PERSON>'s decision to turn to the clinic came on the second straight day of a weather inversion that trapped smoke from fires five miles away over the Old Faithful complex. At times during the two-day period the smoke was so heavy that nearby ridges were obscured. `` We tried bandanas and it worked better than nothing,'' he said. <PERSON> Tek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilgore </PERSON>, a nurse, offered him some surgical masks. `` This may just let us stay a little longer,'' <PERSON> Pardee </PERSON> said on the way back to work. Smoke conditions in the park were moderate to heavy throughout the day Tuesday. While in past days the smoke has hung over Old Faithful like a dense morning mist, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kilgore </PERSON> have n't seen a rise in the number of patients. For one thing, said <PERSON> Kilgore </PERSON>, tourism has gone down as the fires have churned up, and those tourists who have serious respiratory