Israelis also have died. <PERSON> Raed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabra </PERSON>, another federation official, said the union group also makes monthly payments of about $ 120 to families of workers jailed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative, said last week that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was reviewing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s special trade status after the <ORGANIZATION> American-Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Discrimination </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> complained of indiscriminate closures of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> unions. But Israeli officials said the complaint did not recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s security concerns, and <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said the government tried to be sensitive to the social functions of the institutions. `` We have to think twice, because -LRB- the groups -RRB- serve other functions such as improving social conditions and social welfare,'' he said. `` We do n't want to stop those activities, but when it involves the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> we have no choice.'' Both <PERSON> Ayoub </PERSON> and <PERSON> Asali </PERSON> of the lawyers' association said the closing down of their offices would not stop their work on behalf of laborers and professionals. <PERSON> Ayoub </PERSON> said offices of the federation's various unions remained open throughout the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. But the two said seizure of union documents from the offices would impede their organizations' work. <PERSON> Ayoub </PERSON> also said workers' committees were afraid to meet because of earlier arrests of labor leaders He also said he <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> might close union medical clinics. <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said no such action would be taken. The 42-year-old <PERSON> Ayoub </PERSON>