the flight. When he returns to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, more marrow is to be removed and the samples compared. Scientists are trying to determine how to counter bone marrow depletion, which results from prolonged space flight. <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON> also will study motion sickness. Space officials say the endurance tests are a step toward determining whether a manned flight to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>, which they estimate would take three years, is feasible. <LOCATION> Mohmand </LOCATION>, 29, is to take part in experiments to identify oil, gas and other mineral deposits in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and to predict runoff of snow and ice in efforts to alleviate water shortages. His presence represents efforts by the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> to boost the prestige of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s pro-Soviet government as Soviet troops withdraw. The Soviets have agreed to withdraw all their troops by Feb. 15. Half of the 100,000 soldiers have left <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since withdrawal began in May. The flight is the 47-year-old <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON>'s third space mission. He was in space for 175 days in 1979 and took part in a 150-day mission in 1983.
