<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime time TV characters this fall will begin turning down drinks in a coordinated assault on drunken driving initiated by <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> health researchers. Make-believe wives will designate make-believe husbands as non-drinking drivers. Teen-agers who drink will take taxis. And for the next few years polltakers will be trying to find out if viewers are coming under the influence of the push for a `` designated driver.'' `` The goal of the project is to achieve a fundamental change in American social norms regarding drinking and driving,'' <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Winsten </PERSON>, assistant dean of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and director of its <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday night. `` In attempting to achieve that change, we're asking the entertainment, communication and advertising industries to work with us to add momentum behind changes that are already beginning to occur in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he said of the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Winsten </PERSON> said the commitment was made by 13 television studios in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> that are responsible for more than 70 percent of prime time weekly programming on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>. The executives pledged to ask their writers and producers to introduce in their scripts the notion that drinking and driving is taboo, through devices as simple as having drinkers take taxis or saying, `` No thanks, I'm driving.'' <PERSON> Winsten </PERSON> said if the television campaign succeeds, others will be tried. But drunken driving was the priority, he said, reciting these statistics: drunken driving kills 24,000 people each year; studies show as few as two drinks can make a fatal accident twice as likely; two of five Americans will be victims of a drunken driver. In January, <PERSON> Winsten </PERSON> began meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Hollywood </ORGANIZATION> executives to forge the agreements. In April, he won a unanimous endorsement from the board of the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America-West </ORGANIZATION>, whose members write for prime time TV. The networks also agreed to run public service announcements in December to encourage the `` designated driver'' idea, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> advertising firm, <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> DFS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Compton </ORGANIZATION>, has provided advertising research on the designated driver idea, and the <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> said it will donate its services to poll the public to find out whether the TV campaign is working, the newspaper said. Gallup research shows that 78 percent of all drivers would be willing to serve occasionally as designated drivers. <PERSON> Winsten </PERSON> said the campaign will continue for at least three to five years before its real impact will be known. The campaign has precedents, he said. Television networks during the past year or two have been using their characters to encourage the use of seatbelts and to try to take the glamour out of alcohol. But <PERSON> Winsten </PERSON> said he believed this was the first such effort mobilized by a school of public health.
