<HEAD>Criminal Charges to Be Filed if High Court Reinstates Fines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four councilmen refused a third time to change their votes against a housing desegregation plan, as requests from them and the city to continue a stay of contempt fines went to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Unless the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> takes their side, the defiant councilmen will be hit with criminal charges, the state agency that has taken over <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>' finances warned Tuesday. ` It's the city councilmen who are defying the law and putting the city's financial profile at risk, who are putting all the citizens of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> at risk,'' said <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON>, head of the state's <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. The $ 500-a-day fines against the councilmen, along with potentially devastating fines against the city that could reach $ 1 million a day, were imposed by federal Judge <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sand </PERSON>. He found them in contempt Aug. 2, the day after the council's first 4-3 rejection of the court-ordered plan. On Friday, a federal appeals panel upheld the contempt finding but gave <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> a week to take the case to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> before reinstating the penalties. Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> on Tuesday referred the four applications from the councilmen and one from the city to the full <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, according to a court spokesman who gave no indication when the court might rule on a stay. Only after a stay is granted would the court consider the appeal of Sand's contempt finding. At the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s regular meeting Tuesday night, Councilmen <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Longo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chema </PERSON> again rejected a zoning amendment needed to carry out a housing plan that the council had accepted last January. The Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, during a visit to <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, said the city must `` end its illegal resistance'' to the plan. He added that he would be willing to meet with the four but would not specify when that would happen. Three of the four said they would be happy to meet with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, while <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON> said, `` Have him call me.'' Sand ordered the plan to remedy what he determined in a 1985 ruling to have been 40 years of deliberate segregation in housing and education in the city. The plan calls for 200 low-income public housing units to be built in the predominantly white east side of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, with 800 moderate-income apartments to be built throughout the city. Unless a stay is granted, the fines, currently suspended, will be reimposed Friday. The councilmen have paid $ 3,500 each. The city has paid $ 12,700. Its daily payment would resume at $ 12,800 and double daily until it reaches $ 1 million a day, when it will be capped. That would give the city an estimated 70 days until bankruptcy. <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said that if the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal is turned down, she will notify District Attorney <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Vergari </PERSON> that the councilmen are breaking state law by endangering the city's fiscal stability. The four already face possible imprisonment as early as Sunday for contempt. `` I feel it is unfortunate that people elected to uphold the law and defend the law are breaking and defying the law,'' <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. Her remarks came a day after Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he would initiate removal proceedings and urge the councilmen's jailing if the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused the stay.
