<HEAD>Chronology Of Main Political Events Under Pinochet Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a chronology of the main political events in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> since Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> seized power in a coup 15 years ago: Sept. 11, 1973 _ <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> leads the armed forces in a bloody coup that overthrows President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a Marxist elected in 1970. <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> dies in the coup and the new government says he committed suicide. His supporters say he was killed. A four-men Military Junta led by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> takes power and represses supporters of the ousted leftist government. Hundreds of leftists are killed or disappear after being arrested, thousands are sent to concentration camps or into exile. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is closed and political activity prohibited. June 20, 1974 _ <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> becomes supreme chief of the nation, retaining his post as president of the military junta. Oct. 29, 1974 _ Exiled former army commander Gen. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Prats </PERSON> and his wife are killed by a bomb in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, and involvement by Chilean secret police is suspected. The same charge arises when an exiled former foreign minister, <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Letelier </PERSON>, is killed in a Sept 21, 1976, bombing in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> court indicts three high-ranking chilean army officers in the case, but <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> refuses to extradite them. July 9, 1977 _ <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> outlines a far-reaching political and institutional program calling for the military to remain in power at least 11 more years. Jan. 4, 1978 _ <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, faced with growing international and domestic comdemnation of human rights abuse, calls a national referendum to seek support from the Chilean people. He wins the ballot, but opposition leaders charge widespread fraud. June. 20, 1978 _ Air force commander Gen. <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Leigh </PERSON>, a member of the military junta, publicly challenges <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s authority by disagreeing with the government political program <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> ousts <PERSON> Leigh </PERSON> from the junta and forces him into retirement. Sept. 11, 1980 _ <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> wins approval in a referendum for a new constitution that confirms his presidency until March 11, 1989. It also allows him to seek a new period of rule until 1997. The opposition again charges massive fraud in the ballot. March 11, 1981 _ The new constitution goes into effect. May 11, 1983 _ Amid a deep economic crisis, the opposition stages the first of a series of mass protests against the government that left hundreds of dead and thousands arrested. Sept. 6, 1986 _ <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> survives an assassination attempt by a leftist urban guerrilla commando. Five of his bodyguards were killed and 11 wounded when the presidential motorcade is ambushed on a mountain road outside <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>. Aug. 30, 1988 _ The military junta nominates <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> as the sole candidate in an Oct. 5 presidential referendum, sparking widespread protests.
</TEXT>
