<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today, while share prices fell back. The dollar opened at 134.93 yen and inched up to close the day at 134.97 yen, up 0.58 yen from Tuesday's close of 134.39 yen. It moved between 134.80 yen and 135.13 yen, with spot trading estimated at $ 5.9 billion. `` The dollar rose because investors started selling the yen, realizing that interest rates in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> have become the lowest,'' said a foreign exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` The rise in interest rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> last week is finally affecting us,'' he added, speaking on condition of anonymity. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which gained 132.55 points Tuesday, lost 145.70 points, or 0.53 percent, closing the day at 27,365.95. Although the market opened higher, the Nikkei index then reversed direction and lost its earlier gains. The weakening yen was the main cause of the stock market's decline, a trader with a major securities firm in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> said `` Investors got discouraged by the weakening yen, and the trading was very thin,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 400 million shares. Stock prices were lower almost across the board except for a few high-tech issues, such as <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Matsushita </PERSON>, which some investors bought shortly before the closing of the market, the trader said.
