</TEXT>
<HEAD>OREGON:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Forces battling <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s biggest forest fire, the 35,700-acre lightning-sparked Tepee Butte blaze in the state's northeastern corner, were more than doubled Tuesday to 679 people. In the state's eastern high desert, firefighters expected to contain today the <LOCATION> Shirttail </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> fire, 30 miles southeast of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. The fire broke out Monday in an industrial area and burned 5,000 acres of rangeland. More than 52,000 acres have burned since lighting storms touched off fires last week.
