<HEAD>Two Former Continental Illinois Officials Sentenced To Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of two ex-bank officers sentenced to prison for crimes that contributed to the near-collapse of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> held his head and wept as he apologized for the people he had hurt. Sentenced Tuesday were <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> vice president, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, the head of energy lending at the now-defunct <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Square </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, 53, and <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, 38, pleaded guilty June 30 to one criminal charge each for a scheme in which <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> allegedly took kickbacks in exchange for arranging to have <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> buy millions of dollars in risky energy loans from <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. Penn Square failed in 1982, and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> nearly collapsed two years later after an unprecedented run on its deposits. Continental was kept afloat by a $ 4.5 billion government bailout. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> to 3 -LCB- years in prison, despite <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>'s pleas for probation. <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> to a 2-year term. The maximum sentence allowed under their plea bargain was five years. <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, who held his head and choked back tears as he spoke in his own de