now.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Athletes who take high doses of steroids may risk addiction similar to narcotic abuse, doctors warn. In a letter in Thursday's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, doctors report a case of steroid dependence in a man who regularly took four kinds of steroids. The 23-year-old body-builder told doctors he could not stop taking anabolic steroids without experiencing withdrawal symptoms, depression and disabling fatigue. He said he sometimes felt uncontrollably violent, paranoid and suicidal. After a week off steroids, he told doctors that he could n't bear his depression, fatigue and drug craving and intended to resume taking the drugs. `` Some of the clinical features of this patient resemble those frequently observed in cases of opioid dependence,'' the doctors wrote. The letter was written by Drs. <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Projects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Covina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adolescent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Voy </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic Committee. Other researchers have also pointed out that people who abuse steroids may suffer hallucinations, delusions, manic episodes and other temporary mental illness. According to one estimate, as many as 1 million athletes in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may be using steroids to build up their muscles. The drugs retard the tendency of muscle to break down. Steroids can also cause a variety of other side effects, including liver damage, sterility and testicular shrinking.
