<HEAD>Civil War, Food Shortages, Flooding Starving Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of people are fleeing civil war and food shortages in the southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, and many die during the trek northward or in flood-ravaged refugee camps, an opposition party said. An Irish relief official says millions of people face starvation in the south. A statement issued by the Union of Sudanese African Parties, a grouping of southern political parties, did not specify how many people who fled the fierce fighting and famine in the south were dying. `` I would not say by the thousands, but they are dying,'' said a spokesman, who spoke on condition of anomymity. The statement quoted the Bishop of el-Obeid, capital of <LOCATION> Kordofan </LOCATION>, 225 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, as saying people were flocking by the hundreds every day asking for food and help to continue their journey northward. `` This shows you how the food shortages and the long journey, which in some cases is done on foot, can kill women, children and old people,'' the statement said. The Rev. <PERSON> Aengus </PERSON> <PERSON> Finucane </PERSON>, director of the Dublin-based aid agency Concern, called for airlifts of food to regions of the country made inaccessible by the 5-year-old war. `` Two million people are facing death from the ravages of war and starvation,'' <PERSON> Finucane </PERSON> said at <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after returning from a two-week visit to <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s capital. Trains carrying thousands of `` living skeletons'' were arriving in the north every few days, and hundreds of other refugees trekked on foot to camps, he said. About 40 people per day were dying at refugee camps at <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Meriam </LOCATION>, 500 miles from <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Finucane </PERSON>. His organization has 34 workers in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. In 1983, the <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> _ made up mainly of Christians and animists _ took up arms against the Moslem majority government in the north. The <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> claims to control 90 percent of the countryside in the south, with the army in command only in the major cities. Fighting between the army and the rebels has forced an estimated 820,000 southerners to leave their crops and cattle behind and seek shelter around the cities in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, where they become totally dependent on relief food for their livelihood. In <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, about 400,000 refugees live in extreme poverty in tin and canvas shacks around the city. These shantytowns were among the hardest hit areas in the worst floods in the country's history this month that sent the <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> over its banks. The floods have left 1.5 million people homeless, at least 91 dead, tens of thousands of homes destroyed and some of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s most fertile farmland inundated.
