<HEAD>Vietnam To Resume Joint Search For Missing Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> told the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> it is willing to resume joint searches for American servicemen missing in the Vietnam War. The decision was revealed in an Aug. 27 letter from Foreign Minister <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Co </PERSON> <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> to retired Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON>, a special <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential envoy. A text of the letter, carried Tuesday by <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanoi </ORGANIZATION>, was seen today in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> told <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> in an Aug. 3 letter that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> was temporarily suspending full cooperation because of what he called <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s `` hostile policy'' toward <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> cited Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON>'s testimony before a congressional committee in July in which <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON> urged the continued isolation of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s envoy on humanitarian issues relating to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, replied to Thach two days later that <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON>'s testimony merely reflected the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration's `` longstanding viewpoint on relations with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.'' He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would continue implementing previous agreements with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and its humanitarian aid. <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> replied in his Aug. 27 letter that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> `` declaration that it will make the normalization of bilateral relations conditional upon the settlement of the MIA issues is at variance with the agreement between ... -LRB- <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> -RRB- and myself.'' But he said settlement of humanitarian issues `` should be separated from political issues.'' `` With the desire that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government will adopt a suitable attitude ... the Vietnamese side agrees to let the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side participate in joint investigation and survey activities as concerns the issue of American MIAs and is prepared to hold meetings of specialists from the two sides to discuss specific plans from 9 to 12 September 1988,'' <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> agreed in August 1987 that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> would accelerate its accounting of nearly 1,800 Americans listed as missing in action, or MIA, in the Vietnam War, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would give <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> humanitarian aid. <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> told <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> in July that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> would try to resolve 70 top priority MIA cases by the end of this year, and welcomed joint excavations and other searches for remains until October. There have been no joint excavations since the first was conducted in late 1985.
