<HEAD>Continental Cockpit Banter Violated FAA Regulations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Banter between the pilots of a <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> jet before it crashed Nov. 15, killing 28 people, apparently violated federal regulations, officials say. A previously undisclosed portion of the `` black box'' cockpit recording from the DC-9 shows that in the minutes before Flight 1713 crashed, the pilots discussed the dating habits of a woman flight attendant and other matters unrelated to the flight. The tape shows the pilots did not discuss the snow falling at <LOCATION> Stapleton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Both pilots, flight captain <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Zvonek </PERSON> and co-pilot <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruecher </PERSON>, were killed in the crash. Fifty-four people were injured. A <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> rule known as the `` sterile cockpit concept'' prohibits non-essential conversation in the cockpit during ground operations and takeoff preparations. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> said a pilot who violated the rule could be suspended or fined as much as $ 10,000. `` That would definitely be extraneous,'' <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> said Tuesday of the discussions between the two pilots. `` The main point is the cockpit crew is supposed to be concentrating on their primary business of flying the airplane. Distractions can be deadly.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> enacted the regulation in the late 1970s or early 1980s after `` several instances where we found in accidents where flight crews were talking about something other than flying the airplane,'' <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said non-pertinent conversations are common among pilots. `` If the pilots on 1713 were in violation of that reg, 99.9 percent of all commercial pilots in history have violated that reg,'' he said. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> had said previously that the pilots maintained a `` highly skilled, well-disciplined professional cockpit.'' The pilots' conversation has become an issue as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> studies possible causes of the accident, which occurred in a snowstorm. <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoagland </PERSON>, who retired as a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 captain this month, said such cockpit conversations are n't unusual. `` You ca n't just sit and be keyed right on the edge of the aviation experiences all of the time,'' he said. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbon </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arlington </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said that unless pilots anticipate a waiting period, it is unusual for them to spend much time discussing non-flight matters in a plane prpearing to take off in snow. `` If the weather's of concern, usually your attention is taken up by the business at hand,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> is to meet next month to review the accident. The board is studying whether ice or snow buildup on the wings, the experience and training of the pilots and possible turbulence from another aircraft caused the crash.
