 A government spokesman today confirmed that Soviet-based fighter aircraft were used recently to aid Afghan ground troops as they battled for control of the northern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> denied, however, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> charge that the action violated the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords on an Afghan settlement. He told reporters at a regular briefing that the Kremlin responded to an `` urgent situation'' when it sent the aircraft. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> denied another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allegation that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> had sent troops back to <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>, about 30 miles from the Soviet border, after recently withdrawing them. Under the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords signed earlier this year, the Soviets have pulled out half of their 100,000 soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since May 15, and the remainder is scheduled to be withdrawn by Feb. 15. <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, said earlier this week that the Soviets had directed aircraft into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and moved some <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops into <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> from elsewhere within the country. She said the dispatch of aircraft from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was a violation of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said the dispatch of aircraft was justified. `` When the Soviet troops left and part of the troops were still there, counterrevolutionary, anti-governmental gangs began to operate, so count