<HEAD>CPAs Vote to Drop Ethics Ban on Accepting Commissions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Under pressure from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest organization of certified public accountants lifted its 82-year-old ban on CPAs' accepting certain fees and commissions. The ruling council of the 272,000-member <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Certified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pubic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accountants </ORGANIZATION> voted 191-5 Tuesday to drop the prohibition against compensation for non-audit financial planning services. The ban was intended to avoid conflicts of interest among accountants, but officials said that dropping the restriction will benefit the consumer by allowing CPAs to compete against bankers and stockbrokers. `` We've been working on this change for five years, and we're just delighted that it occurred,'' said H.D Vest, an <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, accountant who threatened to sue the institute if it did n't drop the ban The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> last year issued a letter of complaint against the CPA group, threatening legal action unless it allowed accountants to accept commissions for non-audit work. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> contended the ban violated antitrust law. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said the ban effectively prevented CPAs from competing in the financial services market. Since they could not accept commissions, they had no incentive to provide the services. Under the ban, accountants in most states could take no part in financial planning. `` -LRB- The change -RRB- allows consumers to go to one person who knows their situation best, and that one person, the CPA, will make the recommendation,'' Vest said in a telephone interview Tuesday. Vest said consumers will benefit most from the change because it will allow them to get business done `` under one roof.'' Licensing authority is actually held by the individual states, but the institute's code of ethics serves as a model for many state regulatory boards. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> had no immediate comment on the vote, said a woman at the commission's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> offices who did not give her name. Critics of the change focused on the conflict of interest issue, saying accountants could give biased advice to get a bigger fee, Vest said. The institute's policy change allows accountants to earn commissions in several areas, such as helping clients obtain loans, make acquisitions or mergers and devise cost-cutting plans, <PERSON> Vest </PERSON> said. Five states _ <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> _ already allow such commissions. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accountancy </ORGANIZATION>, whose members regulate CPAs, is expected to vote on a similar measure on Sept. 28.
