 Bursts of gunfire resounded in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s southern suburbs today as Shiite Moslem factions rallied to mark the 10th anniversary of the disappearance of their spiritual leader, Imam <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadr </PERSON> A daylong general strike also was observed to mark the occasion. In a separate development, acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, an American-educated, moderate politician, was rushed to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> after a severe asthma attack. Gunmen of the Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, dashed out of the <LOCATION> Bir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> el-Abed </LOCATION> mosque where they were holding their rally as the firing began. They ordered reporters to leave the district. Syrian troops manning checkpoints around the mosque said the firing came from another neighborhood, five blocks to the west. The mainstream <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> faction was holding a separate rally in that area. `` Some militiamen fired their automatic rifles in the air,'' a <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> officer who spoke on condition of anonymity told reporters. `` We are searching the area for them.'' No casualties were reported. Government offices, banks, shops, restaurants and other businesses were closed in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and other towns and cities in south and east <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> as the Shiites observed the strike. The stoppage was called by Amal, which was founded by <LOCATION> Sadr </LOCATION> in 1974 as a social movement seeking better living conditions for the downtrodden Shiite community. The group took up arms a year later, when the Christian-Moslem civil war broke out. <LOCATION> Sadr </LOCATION>, who also headed the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, vanished on Aug. 31, 1978, while on visit to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. Libyan authorities said he left for <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, but Italian authorities denied he ever landed in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Amal has accused the Libyans of holding <LOCATION> Sadr </LOCATION>. The Islamic Amal, another Iranian-backed militia based in east <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, sponsored a third rally in the city of <LOCATION> Baalbek </LOCATION>. There were no reports of any problems there. The 1.2 million Shiites form the largest single sect in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, and their three militant groups are divided mainly over regional alliances and local politics. Amal, headed by Justice Minister <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>, is seeking Christian-Moslem coexistence in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on the basis of political reforms distributing power equally between the two communities. The other two advocate the establishment of an Iran-style Islamic republic. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> also is believed to be an umbrella for underground factions who hold most of the 18 foreigners missing in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> was admitted to the hospital's intensive care unit and was recovering quickly, an attending doctor said. The Sunni Moslem became acting prime minister in June 1987, when Prime Minister <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> <PERSON> Karami </PERSON> was killed in a helicopter explosion. <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> was scheduled to hold a news conference Thursday to elaborate on a political deadlock that has prevented the election of a new Lebanese president. President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>'s six-year term expires on Sept. 23 and he can not run for another term. Christian parliament members boycotted an Aug. 18 election session because the only candidate was former President <PERSON> Suleiman </PERSON> <PERSON> Franjieh </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> who is a staunch ally of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. Christian militias, backed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, are violently opposed to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. Under an unwritten 1943 `` national covenant,'' the president must be a Christian, the prime minister a Sunni Moslem and the parliament speaker a Shiite.
