<HEAD>Chinese Jetliner Skids Off Runway Into Sea; Seven Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with six crew members and one
passenger killed. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``Earlier, small...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HK2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Chinese jetliner with 89 people aboard skidded off a runway while landing in heavy rain today and broke apart in the sea. Officials said seven people were killed, including six crew members trapped in the submerged nose section. Fifteen people were reported injured, and 13 of them were hospitalized in fair or satisfactory condition. The airline said two of 12 Americans on board were injured. A rescue operation at <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s airport involving divers, a flotilla of boats and five helicopters began after Flight 301 plunged into <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> at 9:19 a.m. Later in the day, a huge floating crane lifted the crumpled jetliner from the water, and an investigation into the crash began. The bodies of the six crew members were found in the front part of the plane, according to <PERSON> Tsui </PERSON> <PERSON> Hin-cheuk </PERSON>, divisional commander of the fire services department. Officials said a passenger, a <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> resident identified only by his surname <PERSON> Fung </PERSON>, died of head injuries. Earlier, small rubber rafts with rescue personnel bobbed around the partially submerged wreckage of the British-made Trident jet, which had arrived from <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> province 90 miles to the northwest. Fire engines crowded onto Kai Tak Airport's solitary runway, which juts into the harbor. `` It fell into the sea at the end of the runway,'' police spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Leung </PERSON> said of the jetliner. <PERSON> Tsui </PERSON> <PERSON> Hin-Cheuk </PERSON>, one of those overseeing the search and rescue operation, told reporters the six who died were trapped in the plane's nose section, which was submerged in shallow water just off the end of the runway. The plane, carrying an 11-member Chinese crew, is owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, that nation's flag-carrier. <PERSON> Tsui </PERSON> said one of the plane's engines was on fire when rescue workers arrived, but he did not elaborate. Government-run <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> interviewed one unidentified passenger who said some of the plane's safety belts did not work. `` That's why when the plane landed so hard, people simply were flying,'' the woman told the station. `` I was in the back. It did n't dawn on me that we were really out of control. I was thinking more of ... how I was going to get out.'' <PERSON> Kiyotaka </PERSON> <PERSON> Fukasawa </PERSON>, a 60-year-old Japanese passenger, told reporters that as soon as the plane hit the water, a flight attendant opened an emergency door so passengers could scramble out onto the wing and wait for rescue crews. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said bad weather caused the crash. Airline spokesman <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhengyou </PERSON>, when asked about the cause, said only, `` You know, today the weather is not very good.'' Heavy showers reduced visibility for much of the morning. The nationalities of most of the injured were not known. The airline did not release a passenger list from the plane, which can carry up to 100 people. Hospital officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, identified two of the injured as <PERSON> Heung </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheuk-Wu </PERSON>, a 38-year-old Chinese-American, and <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Allegre </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The airline said the uninjured included 10 Americans, 12 Japanese, 10 Chinese, 10 <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION>, and nationals from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. All incoming and outgoing flights at <LOCATION> Kai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tak </LOCATION>, a major transportation hub for <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, were delayed for nearly seven hours after the crash. It was the worst airline crash at <ORGANIZATION> Kai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tak </ORGANIZATION> since 1967, when a Thai International flight crashed into the harbor, killing 24 of 73 people on board. Two cargo planes have crashed at Kai Tak since, but no one was killed in those accidents.
