<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727, involved in a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> crash Wednesday at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, was initially designed for short to medium routes and was one of the most popular commercial jetliners ever made. The three-engine plane with the distinctive T-tail, no longer manufactured, made its first flight Feb. 9, 1963. It was designed for a maximum passenger capacity of about 130, though later models could carry 189 passengers. The plane has a range of more than 2,500 statute miles. Production ended Aug. 14, 1984, with 1,831 delivered. It is flown by more than 170 carriers. There are various models, all powered by <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> JT8D turbofans. Models include: 727-100, standard passenger seating 94. Length 133' 2'', wingspan 108'. In service Feb. 1, 1964. 727-100C, same size, convertible to all cargo. In service April 23, 1966. 727-100QC, same thing, designed for quick conversions to passenger or cargo. 727-200, Length 153' 2'', wingspan 108', 134 passengers. In service Dec. 14, 1967. 727-200 advanced version, same size, 145 passengers. In service July 1972. 727-200F, all freight version, same size, in service August 1983.
