<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> official said today he does not accept as permanent the decision of King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> to sever his government's ties with the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Tamir </PERSON>, director general of the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters that <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> is well aware that it is impossible to reach a `` final stage solution'' between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> without <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> knows that `` some day he will be called back to negotiate on the final status because without <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, you ca n't solve the problem He knows it very well,'' <PERSON> Tamir </PERSON> said. A month ago, <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> announced he was `` dismantling the legal and administrative links'' between <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, a move that was seen by some as a setback for hopes that a regional peace settlement might be reached. <PERSON> Tamir </PERSON> suggested that it is unrealistic to assume that <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> could sever its historical ties to an area it once ruled, noting that the Camp David agreement envisions a role for <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> in the final stages of negotiations. At the same time, there have been repeated hints over the past month that <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s move may induce the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> to initiate a proposal for peace with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tamir </PERSON>, who is here for talks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, said there is an urgent need to e