<HEAD>IRA Bomb Kills Two in Londonderry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with details on Londonderry
bombing. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``Northern Ireland...'' Trims
thereafter to tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> bomb exploded today in an apartment in a Roman Catholic section of <LOCATION> Londonderry </LOCATION>, killing a man and a woman who accidentally triggered the blast by climbing through a window, police said. The Irish <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> apologized for the killings and said the bomb was intended for British soldiers known to be checking houses in the area. Also today, the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> said three of its members killed by British soldiers on Tuesday were `` on active service,'' the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s term for a guerrilla mission. In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, officials said they caught two men believed to be <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas as they tried to cross the border from the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> with weapons. The pair was apprehended around midnight near a British air base. Police said another man was injured when the bomb demolished the apartment in <LOCATION> Londonderry </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s second-biggest city. A police spokesman, Sgt. <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Winters </PERSON>, said the victims were innocent neighbors who were worried that a young man living in the apartment had not been seen for several days. <PERSON> Winters </PERSON> said the man who climbed inside accidentally triggered the bomb, demolishing the apartment in the mainly Roman Catholic Creggan area. He said police were investigating reports that the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> had kidnapped two occupants of the home several days ago and held them at gunpoint while planting the bomb. The <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Londonderry </LOCATION> unit circulated an apology to local news media saying the bomb was intended for an army search squad. `` Although the operation was carefully planned, it went tragically wrong. At no stage, unfortunately, was it anticipated that a member of the public would enter the flat -LRB- apartment -RRB- through a front window and open a booby-trapped door.'' <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> police and the British army released few details of Tuesday's ambush and killing of the three <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas on a country road at <LOCATION> Drumnakilly </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tyrone </LOCATION>. The spot was only eight miles from <LOCATION> Ballygawley </LOCATION>, where an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> bomb blew up a military bus Aug. 20, killing eight soldiers and injuring 27. British media reports said commandos of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s elite <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> regiment ambushed and killed the three men as they prepared to attack a soldier of the locally recruited <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regiment </ORGANIZATION>. The police and army refused to comment on the reports. <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>, legal political wing of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday the slain men were <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> members. It identified them as <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> and brothers <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON>. Today, it released a statement from the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Ulster </ORGANIZATION> battalion saying the men were killed while `` on active service.'' The killings were seen as the start of a tougher British policy to combat increased <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> attacks. So far this year, the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> has killed 27 membe