<HEAD>Public Schools to Offer Religion or Mandatory Study Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Public school children who do n't want to take daily religion class will have to replace that hour with `` equivalent alternative material,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> has ruled. Tuesday's ruling by the <ORGANIZATION> supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> administrative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> court </ORGANIZATION> that advises the government on prospective legislation reversed a 1987 decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lazio </ORGANIZATION> in which students were given three choices: an hour of religion, an hour of an alternative study or the option not to attend either. Just what subjects might be offered for the `` equivalent alternative'' hour and who would be responsible for teaching them is still undecided. The ruling was criticized for not first legislating national guidelines for the alternative hour. Each school can decide the content of the alternative study. Religious instruction in this overwhelmingly Roman Catholic country was made optional in a 1984 revision of the Concordat, or Italian-Vatican treaty, but there has been no standard formula for how such classes should be scheduled or what to do with students not taking it. The issue developed into a church-state struggle last year. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> pushed for a mandatory alternative class, saying students would be discouraged from attending religious classes if allowed to leave school. `` Lay'' political forces objected, saying it would compromise the optional future of religious instruction. In 1987 more than 90 percent of public school students reportedly had signed up for <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> teaching.
</TEXT>
