<FIRST>u i AM-PeoplePower Bjt   08-31 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People Power, Bjt,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Latest Example of `People Power' Against Authoritarians in
Asia</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It is happening again in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>: masses of people mounting a sustained campaign of demonstration and protest against an authoritarian government. For several weeks it has been <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. A year ago it was <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. In February 1986, `` people power'' in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> ended the 20-year presidency of <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and drove him into exile. Popular protest developed differently in each case, under markedly different circumstances, but brought changes that were breathtaking for all three nations. There were signs that crowds of demonstrators in both <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> drew inspiration from the Philippine example. Some South Korean protesters cited the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> as a model of an Asian nation throwing off oppressive rule without upsetting the entire basis of society or destroying the economy. Foreign tourists emerging from <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> told reporters that many <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION>, repressed for 26 years, found parallels with the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which had close ties with the former regimes in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, says it welcomes more representative government in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. After Burmese authorities lifted martial law last Wednesday and said they would consider holding free elections, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said: `` Certainly we welcome this movement toward democracy.'' <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON>, an assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee in May: `` Politically, progress toward increasingly representative government continues apace in the <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. In short, events in the region have been going our way.'' Nonetheless, anti-American demonstrations have occurred as those who demonstrated against their governments turned to protests of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces stationed in the two countries and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> support for the former leaders. <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials say <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> will face more difficult relations with countries whose governments become more democratic. <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> followed an isolationist course under the `` Burmese way to socialism'' of Ne Win, who seized power in a coup in 1962. He resigned late in July and students led protests for democracy, economic reform and release of prisoners. Ne Win's successor, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, jailed dissidents and soldiers shot to kill in an unsuccessful attempt to stop demonstrations by hundreds of thousands of people. <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks joined students in reading pro-democracy proclamations. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> resigned after 17 days, to be replaced by civilian attorney <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, and the turmoil continues. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, professor of Japanese studies at <ORGANIZATION> Sophia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and a widely published commentator on <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> politics, said it was `` encouraging and remarkable that such latent people power existed'' in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. `` We had thought they were a demoralized and docile population, unhappy about governmental inefficiency but tolerating it,'' he said. `` It turned out they had as much guts and bravery as the people in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>.'' The Burmese did not have leaders to provide a focus as, for instance, the Filipinos had in <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. She is the widow of <PERSON> Benigno </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who was assassinated when he returned home to oppose <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, and became president when <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> fled. Another difference was that a military revolt against <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> coincided with the popular uprising, while the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> military was used against protesters. In <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, street battles last summer between huge crowds and riot police led to major concessions toward democracy from the military-backed government but did not overthrow it. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON>, the outgoing president, accepted opposition demands that included direct presidential elections, greater freedom of speech and release of many political prisoners. Whether the revolt in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> will bring greater democracy is not yet clear, but Asians have shown that great potentional power lies in coordinated mass effort in a region of 3 billion people. <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s most noted proponent of mass action was <PERSON> Mohandas </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. He led vast throngs in demonstrations against British colonial rule in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, which became independent in 1947.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorson </PERSON> is the <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> news editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
