<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDALUSIA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury today impeached Florala Mayor H.T. <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> on charges of neglect of duty and incompetence, removing him from an office he used to publicize `` voodoo'' antics and to pardon scores of drunken drivers. The 85-year-old mayor ran out of the <LOCATION> Covington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> courtroom after the circuit court jury announced its verdict. His attorney, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Prestwood </PERSON>, said he would seek a new trial for the mayor, who testified that he pardoned dozens of convicted offenders because he's `` soft hearted.'' After one hour of deliberation this morning, the jury ruled that <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> should be removed from office because he's incompetent and neglected his duty. The verdict means he was immediately ousted, Circuit Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> said. Prosecution witnesses have depicted <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> as a man who undermined the law by abusing his pardon power during the last four years. He is accused of pardoning more than 100 traffic offenders, including 27 drunken drivers. But <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON>, taking the stand Tuesday to defend his performance in office, said people came to him with sad stories and he was just trying to help them. `` I'm just a little soft hearted,'' the former tire store owner testified. The mayor of <LOCATION> Florala </LOCATION>, a town of about 5,000 on the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> border 20 miles south of <LOCATION> Andalusia </LOCATION>, drew national attention with his July proclamation of `` National Voodoo Week'' and his earlier purported attempt to scare the police chief by sprinkling so-called `` voodoo powder'' around City Hall, council chambers and down corridors to the jail. However, <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> testified that he did not believe in voodoo and the yellow powder he spread at City Hall was sulfur powder not meant to harm anyone physically. After the media reported the incident, the mayor said he decided to capitalize on publicity. `` I do n't even know what voodoo means,'' he testified. `` I made a mistake in the way I did it.'' Before taking the stand Tuesday, he told reporters: `` Satan is trying to destroy <PERSON> Florala </PERSON>'s government. I love Florala.'' <PERSON> Prestwood </PERSON> said during closing arguments on the second day of the trial that it would be cruel to impeach <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON>, whose term ends Oct. 3. `` They've done everything in the book to make H.T. <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> look bad.'' <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> was depicted by prosecution witnesses as a man who undermined the law by abusing his power to pardon drunken drivers. `` I have more power than <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> was quoted as saying by City Clerk <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooten </PERSON>. In the state's closing arguments, Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Valeska </PERSON> said no one in <LOCATION> Florala </LOCATION> expected <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> `` would go power crazy.'' `` For him to have one more hour in office flies in the face of our system of government,'' <PERSON> Valeska </PERSON> said. Later, state Attorney General <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegelman </PERSON> described the situation in <LOCATION> Florala </LOCATION> as `` the most abusive case I've ever heard of in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.''
