<HEAD>Republicans Criticize Dukakis on Pardons But Records Show GOP Not
as Tough</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has come under <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> fire for granting pardons to more than 230 ex-convicts since 1983, but records show he has been tougher on the issue than his <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> predecessors. The <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, in a report released Tuesday, said the governor pardoned 232 people between 1983 and 1987, clearing their records of crimes ranging from manslaughter _ five cases _ to breaking and entering _ 136 cases. Twenty-one of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' pardons _ nearly one out of 10 _ were granted to people convicted of selling or possessing with intent to sell drugs. The council, a non-profit, research organization founded and initially funded by state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamie </PERSON>, claims no ties to the Republican leader. And <PERSON> Bull </PERSON> <PERSON> Purdun </PERSON>, president of the council, said it was not trying to make `` an overall judgment'' about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. But state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> Executive Director <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> said the report `` is a clear indication that <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is a very liberal, left-wing person. He says one thing about being tough on crime and he does another.'' However, figures provided by the governor's statehouse press office show that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has granted fewer pardons than his predecessors. Republican governor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Volpe </PERSON> granted 1,324 pardons between 1965 and 1968, and GOP <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sargent </PERSON> granted 1,755 pardons between 1969 and 1974. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> granted 552 pardons during his first term from 1975 to 1978. He was followed by <PERSON> Democrat-later-to-turn-Republican </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, who granted 211 pardons from 1979 to 1982. Although <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> granted more pardons between 1983 and 1987 than <PERSON> King </PERSON> did during his administration, the number of pardons <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> allowed during a comparable four-year period was actually less _ 192. The 232 pardons granted by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> between 1983 and 1987 came from 550 requests submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pardons </ORGANIZATION>, a committee of the state <ORGANIZATION> Parole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. The full parole board recommended 247 of those be granted, and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> rejected 15 of them. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, executive assistant to the state <ORGANIZATION> Parole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said the board considers a pardon `` an extraordinary form of relief.'' `` It is founded on the principle that people ought to be able to put their problems behind them if they have exhibited extended periods of good citizenship and deserve forgiveness by the commonwealth,'' he said. The pardoning process is an extensive one that includes input from the courts, the police and the prosecutors familiar with each applicant. Besides the <ORGANIZATION> Parole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, the governor's legal counsel and the eight-member elected Governor's Council review the applications. While the number of pardons has been decreasing, the number of criminals being sent to state prisons has increased by 40 percent between 1983 and 1987 and the crime rate has dropped 13.4 percent, said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> press aide. In 1983, 2,035 people were sent to state prisons. In 1987, there were 2,853. Of that increase in 818 inmates, 72 percent of them were convicted of drug-related crimes, <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> said. `` Very simply there are more people going to jail and there are hard clear increases in the number of drug offenders going to jail,'' <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> said. `` And by same token, we are looking at fewer pardons.''
