<HEAD>Report: Prosecution Against Writers Continues In 29 Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Persecution against writers continues in at least 29 nations despite notable improvements in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, with an estimated 305 authors imprisoned worldwide, a report said Wednesday. `` In all parts of the world, there are cases of censorship or attempts at censorship,'' said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> P.E.N. </ORGANIZATION>, the London-based association of writers and literary figures that is meeting in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and issued the report. The report from P.E.N.'s influential `` Writers in Prison'' committee said the number of novelists, poets, playwrights and journalists known to be imprisoned in 1988 was 305, or 35 less than one year ago. `` The decrease is almost entirely explained by the new policy against dissidents in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION>,'' the report said. `` In 1983, 93 Soviet writers and journalists were reported imprisoned, in forced psychiatric confinement or internal exile. Today the corresponding number is 20.'' `` Despite the fact that numbers in prison are diminishing and there are improvements in the treatment of writers in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said conditions worsened in countries such as <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` There is no solution,'' said King, a British novelist and playwright, `` because there is no solution to human wickedness.'' He said the figures may be too low in some cases because information is not available from every country. King said P.E.N. would continue pressing for the release of those denied freedom of expression, in particular <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <PERSON> T