<FIRST>r i AM-Stakhanov     08-31 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stakhanov,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper says Hero Worker's Life Ruined by Soviet Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and his successor, <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, drove the nation's showcase hard worker to drink and ruined his family by promoting him to paper-shuffling jobs, a newspaper reported Wednesday. <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> was quickly ignored after his record-breaking coal mining feat in the 1930s that made him a hero worker, the labor newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Trud </ORGANIZATION> said. `` <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> was thrown out and forgotten,'' <PERSON> Trud </PERSON> said. `` That is how short the administrative-command -LRB- system's -RRB- memory turned out to be. The Stalinist system needed a symbol, a poster, and not a living person.'' <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> became a legend in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for setting a world production record for coal. On Aug. 31, 1935, he drilled 102 tons of coal in six hours, 14 times the norm for one shift. Western historians say the feat, performed at a <LOCATION> Donetsk </LOCATION> basin mine, was contrived. They say all other work was stopped in <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON>'s section of the mine and that a whole gang performed auxiliary work that normally had to be done by the man at the coal face. This explanation has not been reported in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> media, apparently so as not to diminish the value of the feat. The achievement started a nationwide `` speed-up'' movement in which workers, nicknamed `` Stakhanovites,'' competed for bonuses and privileges by setting fantastic output records. Wednesday's article represented another attempt under Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or openness, to recount history more accurately. It also was another blow to <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who is widely criticized in the official media now for developing a `` cult of personality,'' killing millions of people including loyal <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members in bloody purges, and overcentralizing the Soviet economy. Like other Soviet leaders recalling the hard-working spirit of <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has stressed the need to increase productivity. But _ in addition to working harder _ he has promised people a program of improved technology and accompanied the calls for higher quantity production with a drive for better quality goods. <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> received many awards, a better apartment and was wined and dined by Soviet officials including <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. He did not, however, fare well in the long term, <PERSON> Trud </PERSON> said. The newspaper said that in 1936, <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> was torn away from his favorite work and brought to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to become a bureaucrat. He was made section chief of socialist competitions and awards. `` For 25 whole years after that, his name disappeared from newspaper and magazine pages, from documentary films. His voice was n't heard from a speaker's stand,'' <PERSON> Trud </PERSON> said. The new job turned <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> into an alcoholic, the newspaper said. `` He did n't do anything in particular. With the strong hands that were created for a man's real work, he was shuffling paper and in the evening not infrequently poured himself vodka of bitterness,'' Trud said. His lot did not improve under <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, who came to power in 1953. When a foreign visitor asked the Soviet leader in 1957 what had become of <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON>, he said the hero worker was still in <LOCATION> Donbass </LOCATION>, the area where he set the production record, according to Trud. But <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> actually was in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, and when <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> learned of this later, he had the miner sent back to the region. <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> only had 24 hours' notice of the move and left his wife and children behind in the capital. Local officials ignored him. He died a lonely and depressed man in 1977, <PERSON> Trud </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> still serves as an example for Soviet workers, Trud said, and for that `` will remain in the people's memory as an outstanding worker and patriot.''
