<HEAD>Warring Moslems, Christians Offer Differing Solutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The warring Moslem and Christian communities of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> proposed contradictory solutions Wednesday to the 13-year-old conflict that has claimed 130,000 lives. Justice Minister <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>, head of the Syrian-backed mainstream <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> movement, called for an end to the `` First Republic'' that has given Maronite Catholics dominance over <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> since independence was gained from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> 45 years ago. `` I hereby declare the end of the <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> by burying the system of the 1943 covenant and the creation of the Second Lebanese Republic based on <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s Arab calling, sovereignty, independence and justice,'' <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> was referring to an unwritten covenant under which the Maronites controlled the presidency, the army, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and the judiciary. The charter gave the Shiites the post of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> speaker and the Sunni Moslems the prime minister's portfolio. <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> threatened that Syrian-backed Moslem and leftist factions would not permit presidential elections if the demanded reforms were not accepted before Sept. 23, when the six-year term of President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> expires. But <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>, commander of the right-wing Christian Lebanese forces militia, rejected <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>'s proposals. `` We are ready, after the presidential elections, to meet with all the Lebanese factions anywhere in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> to discuss ` entente.' Presidential elections should be held first,'' <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> said. Entente, in Lebanese political parlance, refers to a formula of coexistence accepted by the various warring factions. Parliament failed Aug. 18 to muster a quorum to elect a president to succeed <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> when only 38 deputies showed up at <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The only serious candidate was Syrian-backed former President <PERSON> Suleiman </PERSON> <PERSON> Franjieh </PERSON>. Moslem and leftist factions accused the Lebanese Forces of preventing parliamentary deputies from taking part in the session, in order to block the election of <PERSON> Franjieh </PERSON>, a personal friend of Syrian President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON>. <PERSON> Franjieh </PERSON>, 78, holds <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> responsible for the June 1978 killing of his elder son, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON>; <PERSON> Tony </PERSON>'s wife; and 3-year-old daughter, along with 30 followers in a raid on the family's summer mansion in the northern town of <LOCATION> Ehden </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gegea </PERSON> made his remark at a news conference in <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> as <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> addressed a mass rally in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to commemorate the 10th anniversary of the disappearance of the Shiites' religious leader in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, Imam <PERSON> Moussa </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadr </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Sadr </LOCATION>, who founded <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> in 1974 and headed the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, disappeared Aug. 31, 1978, during a visit to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. Amal has accused the Libyans of holding him. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> denied the charge. <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> called on Moslem and leftist militias to `` jointly confront the threat and achieve victory.'' `` We should have the closest possible ties with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> added. <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> called on <PERSON> Franjieh </PERSON> to withdraw his candidacy because `` the Syrians want to ruin <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' The Lebanese Forces, known for their close ties with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, are <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s main foe in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, the principal power broker in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, has about 40,000 troops in eastern and northern parts of the country and in west and south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>.
