<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Plane Crash Kills At Least 11 At Dallas-Fort Worth Airport</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with witnesses reporting passengers chanted `Get up'
from another plane, survivor saying wing was red-hot. EDITS
throughout to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos DN4,5, NY35, LaserColor DN6, LaserGraphic NY29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> jetliner carrying more than 100 people crashed and burned on takeoff today at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, killing at least nine and injuring more than 30, officials said. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 en route to <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> went down in hazy sunshine, broke in two and burst into flames on a flat, grassy field near the runway. Many passengers climbed to safety through a blackened hole in the top of the cabin. Passengers on another flight who watched in horror as the plane tipped to one side and went down chanted `` Get up! Get up!,'' a witness said. `` There was pandemonium. People were jumping on the plane's wing and burning themselves on it because it was so red hot,'' said a survivor, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammack </PERSON>. `` We got out of the way fast because we thought it was going to explode.'' `` You could see the fuel running down the window and down the wing, and I was n't going to get burned,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said at least nine people were killed and that about 60 survivors were healthy enough to continue on their way. The three pilots survived, although one suffered a severe back injury, he said. At least 32 people were admitted to seven hospitals, hospital officials said, but their condition was not immediately known. Other passengers were treated and released. Most of the injured suffered burns, cuts or broken bones. `` The plane had slid sideways about the last 100 yards on the ground. It was n't a violent crash. It was n't cartwheeling or anything like that,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Weeks </PERSON>, who works for an airport shuttle bus service and talked to some of the injured. `` They had no idea what happened,'' Weeks said. The fire was brought under control quickly, but the partially blackened, split-open fuselage smoldered more than an hour after the 9:03 a.m. accident. Flight 1141, which originated in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, carried more than 97 passengers and seven crew members, but the exact number was not known because infants are not on passenger lists, <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said. `` The important thing is that the airplane was 1,000 feet from the end of the runway,'' <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said. `` This had to aid rescue efforts.'' <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> earlier reported 15 and then 11. He said those figures were based on erroneous reports from hospital officials and people at the scene. Investigators had no immediate indication of the cause of the crash, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. However, a source involved in the federal investigation said early indications were that the jet took an unusually long time to become airborne, that it climbed to only about 80 feet, and that the left wing struck the runway first. The source spoke on condition of anonymity. An <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> team of investigators was sent to the scene. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 is one of the most popular commercial jetliners ever made, flown by more than 170 carriers. <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Waugh </PERSON>, an uninjured passenger, said the plane `` never got in the air.'' `` I heard a noise _ I knew something was wrong,'' <PERSON> Waugh </PERSON> said. Within a minute, the plane was in flames, he said. The plane broke in two, and passengers began scrambling through the roof, he said. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnett </PERSON>, an attorney from <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, said he was on a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> flight that had just landed when the plane went down. `` It was tipping as it was taking off. It was already tipping to the right and then, as it crossed in front of us, it never was able to get altitude,'' he said. `` A lot of people on the left side of our plane we're saying, ` Get up, get up' when they saw it coming right in front of us.'' <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said he saw the plane from his window before it crashed. `` I noticed the tail was sort of hanging down, like, you know, it should n't have been,'' he said. `` And then I saw red sparks starting at the back of the tail, and I thought that's not its light, that's a fire. Then I watched it put its tail into the ground and exploded in a huge ball of fire.'' Ambulances took injured from the site, and fire trucks sprayed foam on the wreckage. Rescue teams in asbestos suits walked through the wreckage, looking for passengers and spraying water on sections still aflame. Ambulances drove onto and off the field where the jet crashed. Several helicopters also flew in and out. The accident is the second at <ORGANIZATION> DFW </ORGANIZATION> involving <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> in three years. On Aug. 2, 1985, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> Flight 191 crashed as it approached a runway during a violent thunderstorm, killing 137 people, including a motorist. The crash injured 25 others. The L-1011 jet was on a flight from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. Investigators determined that there was a wind shear, a violent change in wind direction that can rob a plane of lift On May 24, a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 of the Costa Rican airline <ORGANIZATION> LACSA </ORGANIZATION> exploded in flames on takeoff from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. No one was seriously injured.
