<HEAD>Government Threatens Action Against Occupiers of State Buildings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government threatened protesters who have occupied government buildings, and striking public employees planned a huge march Thursday against 26 years of authoritarian rule. Organizers said four columns of demonstrators marching from different areas would converge on Bandoola Gardens, <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>'s largest park, for a rally Employees of more than 120 government departments and state-owned corporations formed the <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strike </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday. It was the fourth illegal association created in three days. Students and dock workers have formed illegal unions and 21 elder statesmen created a <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> led by <PERSON> Win </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, 72, who was president in Prime Minister U Nu's government. U Nu, 81, was the man ousted in the 1962 military coup that ended <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> democracy. He has been named `` patron'' of the group. <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> radio broadcast an official statement that said the government has allowed peaceful assembly and marches, but added: `` In some towns, <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- local government -RRB- offices and other government buildings are illegally occupied by the people. Illegal occupants must vacate the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> offices and government buildings immediately or face the consequences.'' It did not describe the consequences. The statement was signed by <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON>, secretary to the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, as the Cabinet is called. President <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>'s government has said a special session of the <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's only legal political group, will be held Sept. 12 to consider holding a referendum on one-party rule. Protesters from all segments of <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> society have rejected that and demand formation of an interim government to bring back democracy. A general strike has paralyzed <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and other cities. Protesters apparently have taken over the local adminsitrations of <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> in southernmost <LOCATION> Mergui </LOCATION> state and some other towns. Local adminstrations _ the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Councils </ORGANIZATION> _ and officers of the ruling party have resigned in some areas, with security and other duties being taken up by residents and <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks. One Burmese analyst described the situation as anarchic. He said Wednesday that people live in daily fear and suspense amid rumors of bombings, arson, looting and impending coups. Turmoil began when <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> resigned July 23, after imposing more than a quarter-century of isolation and economic ruin after the coup. He was succeeded by <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, a hardliner held responsible for bloody repression of previous protests. Soldiers shot into crowds of demonstrators and at least 112 people were killed in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> alone, according to official figures. Unofficial estimates put the number at several times that. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, a civilian lawyer, replaced <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> after 17 days and the violence abated, but protests continued. <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> radio said more than 1,500 prisoners were released Tuesday and Wednesday from Insein jail in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and a prison at <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. That brings to about 8,700 the number reported freed from the two jails. Riots were reported last week at those and five other jails, where smaller numbers of prisoners have been released. The official radio urged striking workers to resume their jobs at the nation's two oil refineries, at <LOCATION> Syriam </LOCATION> 10 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> in central <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. `` As petrol and diesel oil can not be refined and sold, transportation of commodities by car and rail and commuter transport services will no longer be possible,'' it said. `` Hence the working people will have to bear the high cost of goods.'' Officials accompanied by soldiers began house-to-house searches Tuesday for engineers of the Syriam refinery to force them back to work, but an engineer told the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday none had been found. He said he and his colleagues were in hiding and would continue the strike until an interim government was formed. About 150 refinery engineers, technicians and chemists are on strike, he said. Sources said more than 5,000 employees of the Syriam refinery, led by the plant manager, marched in the town Sunday shouting anti-government slogans. Workers at <LOCATION> Syriam </LOCATION>, which had produced 26,000 barrels of petroleum products a day, walked out in mid-August when student protesters called for a nationwide general strike. Military engineers tried unsuccessfully to operate the plant.
