<DATELINE>HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At first blush, it sounds like a pretty good deal. If you do n't mow your lawn in <LOCATION> Hempstead </LOCATION>, the town will do it for you. Ah, but there are strings attached to the new lawn law, which was approved by town supervisors Tuesday. For starters, the town will charge errant landowners a fee for municipal mowing. And town officials have the right to tack on a $ 250 fine and throw the offender in jail. The fee has n't been determined. The beautification law, which goes into effect this fall, specifies that the town will cut any lawn in which the grass is more than 8 inches high. It also empowers the town to remove abandoned vehicles from private property. Officials wo n't prowl through neighborhoods with tape measures, said Presiding Supervisor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondello </PERSON>. But action will be taken against people whose neighbors complain enough, or whose lawn is obviously high enough to be unsightly, he said.
