o the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the countries invited. The message repeated Soviet and Afghan charges that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is violating the agreement by interfering in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s affairs, and noted that 73 complaints about this have been filed with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has rebel bases and helps funnel U.S.-supplied arms to the insurgents. The Afghan government is hoping a leadership change in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will mean more cooperation in peace efforts. `` We hope that the new Pakistani government, realizing the need for an above-board approach to the international agreements signed by the country, will take steps toward improving relations between the two neighboring Moslem states and normalizing the situation in the region as a whole,'' <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>, a strong backer of the rebels, was killed in a plane crash Aug. 17. He was succeeded by <PERSON> Ghulam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishaq </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Under the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords, the Soviets have pulled out half of their 100,000 soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since May 15, and the remainder is scheduled to be withdrawn by Feb. 15.
