 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Wednesday urged the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to stop sending planes from its territory to strike at U.S.-backed guerrillas in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The call came on the eve of a meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> between Undersecretary of State <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> and Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON>. The two diplomats are meeting to discuss a series of regional issues affecting the superpowers' client states around the world, but the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> question is expected to be at the top of the agenda. On Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> accused the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> of violating the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords for the pullout of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by sending its planes to bomb the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> rebels around the northern Afghan city of <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>. A government spokesman in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> confirmed that Soviet-based fighter aircraft were used to aid Afghan ground troops battling for <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> but denied the action violated the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> also denied another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allegation that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> had sent troops back to <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>, about 30 miles -LRB- 50 kms -RRB- from the Soviet border, after recently withdrawing them. But Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> dismissed <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON>'s denial, saying, `` I'm sticking where I was on this question yesterday We said that these raids came from bases inside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Therefore, in our view, it was a violation.'' She cited a clause in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords which she said commits the Soviets to `` refrain from any form of interference or intervention in the internal affairs of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> declined to elaborate, saying only, `` obviously the Soviets have admitted that they have used aircraft in the bombing raids in <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> from areas inside <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Let me repeat, we wish they'd stop it.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> reiterated that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was in the process of preparing a complaint for the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Good Offices Mission which monitors the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> pact. The agreement signed last April calls for the pullout of all Soviet troops by Feb. 15. The Soviets have already complied with an Aug. 15 deadline for withdrawing half of their estimated 115,000 troops following more than eight years of occupation. The Soviets have repeatedly complained to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Pakistani violations of the pact in connection with supplies to the Mujahedeen. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says it will keep arming the rebels as long as the Soviets supply the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government.
