<HEAD>State Court Leaves Biaggi On Ballot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state's top court refused Wednesday to consider removing former Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> from the state's Democratic primary ballot, despite his resignation and conviction on corruption charges The decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> not to hear the appeal by <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s primary opponents means the popular <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Democrat </LOCATION>'s name will almost certainly be on the ballot Sept. 15 even though he has said he's not a candidate. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, 70, was in his 10th term when he resigned his congressional seat Aug. 5, the day after he was convicted on federal racketeering, extortion and bribe-taking charges in connection with the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> defense scandal. Because of <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s popularity, some <ORGANIZATION> Bronx </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders believe there's a strong chance he could win the primary election. In the heavily <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> district, a primary victory often guarantees a November election victory, and that's especially true in this case because <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> also has the Republican nomination. If <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> is re-elected to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, it's expected that he would resign again rather than face the possibility of not being seated by his former colleagues. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had been poised to begin expulsion hearings against him when he resigned in August. In the wake of Wednesday's action, the only way <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> could get off the Sept. 15 Democratic primary ballot is by death, being nominated for a judgeship or moving out of the state. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s opponents in the Sept. 15 Democratic primary, state <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON>