<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-US     08-31 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Protest US Navy Ships Capable Of Launching Nuclear
Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HIROYUKI KACHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOKOSUKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of protesters shouted from hilltops and waved banners on boats Wednesday when two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships that can launch nuclear missiles sailed into the home port of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 7th Fleet. The ships are the first to be stationed in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with launchers for Tomahawk missiles, which are made in both nuclear and non-nuclear versions. `` Get out from <LOCATION> Yokosuka </LOCATION>!'' about 100 people shouted in English at the gates of the naval base as the Ticonderoga-class guided missile cruiser USS Bunker Hill and the destroyer USS Fife arrived in the port 28 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. A coast guard official said the warships arrived without incident. Forty-two coast guard patrol boats escorted the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships into the port to prevent the approach of 28 small boats carrying protesters and banners reading `` No Tomahawks,'' the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> forbids the production, possession, or introduction into the country of nuclear weapons. Nearly 200,000 people died in the Japanese cities of <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dropped the first atomic bombs to end World War II. After the ships arrived, more protesters from civic and peace groups, labor unions and the Japanese <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> staged separate rallies at a park overlooking the port, outside the naval base and elsewhere, carrying placards and shouting slogans. Police reported no arrests. Protesters said the biggest rally, sponsored by the communists, drew an estimated 1,000 people. On Tuesday, <LOCATION> Yokosuka </LOCATION>'s 48-member city assembly unanimously passed a resolution urging the government to keep out the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships. The city's mayor and the