<HEAD>100,000 Forced From Homes By Flooding In Six States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Flooding in six northern states has forced about 100,000 people from their homes, the president's office said Wednesday The flooding has destroyed hundreds of thousands of acres of crops and killed thousands of farm animals, according to televised news reports. President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> has asked <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s congress to approve $ 8 million in disaster assistance to the states of <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlantico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sucre </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Magadalena </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> and Bolivar. Heavy rain is expected to continue for the next few days, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s weather service said Wednesday. The biggest river in the region, the <LOCATION> Magdalena </LOCATION>, overflowed its banks Saturday. The flooding has caused an increase in the number of mosquitoes, the public health department for the state of <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> said in a news release. Malaria and dengue fever, both carried by mosquitoes, is common in the <LOCATION> Magdalena </LOCATION> river region. Twenty people have been bitten by poisonous snakes in <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> since flooding began there two weeks ago, the health department said.
