000 employees was blocked this week by a federal judge. Delta began corporate life as the world's first cropdusting service _ <ORGANIZATION> Huff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dusters </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> Huff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Ogdensburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>. Then in 1928, the company, led by <PERSON> Collett </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolman </PERSON>, broke away from the parent company to form <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> with headquarters in <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> Passenger service began in 1929 with 90 mph flights from <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Woolman </PERSON>, who ran the company until his death in 1966, set the tone for <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> including a unique tradition of having pilots greet passengers as they leave each flight. The company changed its name in 1930 to <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and later to <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and moved headquarters to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> in the early'40s. For the annual meeting, however, the company leaves its headquarters at <ORGANIZATION> Hartsfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> and returns to <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s growth was spurred in the early years as it added routes in the South and merged with other airlines in 1953 and 1972. But the biggest step came in 1987, when <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> completed an $ 860 million merger with <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, making it the nation's third largest airline in terms of numbers of passengers carried. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, which has 48,000 employees, posted a profit of $ 306.83 million on $ 6.92 billion in revenues during the fiscal year ended June 30.
