<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of government postal workers sealed mail boxes, stopped sorting letters and walked off their routes Wednesday to protest bonus payments that vary by region. Private delivery companies welcomed the extra business, saying it will prove they can compete. The Union of Communication Workers called a 24-hour nationwide strike, but the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> disputed the union's claim that nearly all its 140,000 letter carriers and letter sorters had stopped working. `` It's very patchy, a patchy situation,'' said <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a Royal Mail spokeswoman. `` While there's certainly support for the strike, nevertheless quite a number of staff have turned up for work.'' She said the post office had repeatedly offered to continue talks with the union and had been `` as flexible as we can.'' The union's other 60,000 members either work for the state telephone monopoly or for the post office in administration or counter services, which were not involved in the dispute, said a union spokesman. Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said mail was being sorted and delivered in some areas, particularly the southeast and southwest, although she did not have figures for how many employees had shown up for work. Counter services were not disrupted at any of the striking <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> post offices in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, although letter boxes had been sealed, she said. It was the first national strike at <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> since a 1971 walkout which collapsed after 47 days. The stoppage increased demands for Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservative government to end the Royal Mail's near-monopoly on the delivery of letters and parcels Since she came to power in 1979, her government has sold off to private enterprise large sectors of state-owned assets under its denationalization program. The Royal Mail has the exclusive right to collect, sort and deliver all mail with a postal charge of less than one pound -LRB- $ 1.60 -RRB-. The cost of mailing an ordinary letter in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> through the Royal Mail is 18 pence -LRB- 30 cents -RRB-. <ORGANIZATION> TNT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mailfast </ORGANIZATION>, a company claiming to be the largest private carrier in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, said business rose 500 percent on Wednesday and was expected to produce long-term benefits. `` People are getting a bit upset about the threat of strikes all the time,'' said general manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartle </PERSON>. `` More and more people who come over to us are tending to stay.'' <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON>, general secretary of the union, said the union was `` going to throw the nation's mail into chaos.'' The dispute concerns bonus payments for new recruits in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and southeastern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, where living costs are higher than in the rest of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and where the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> has trouble recruiting and keeping staff because of high employment and competition for staff. The union wants the bonuses paid to all new recruits throughout the country or not paid at all. <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON> said he fears the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> management eventually wants to introduce differentials in basic pay for different areas and end national pay bargaining agreements. The bonuses range from $ 12.67 to $ 33.80 a week. The <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> said that with the bonuses, first-year recruits in central <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> earn a basic $ 206 a week. It said the average wage for all postal workers in central <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> was $ 405 a week.
