<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American oilmen are negotiating quietly in hopes of resuming Libyan operations if the next <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration ends or modifies the economic embargo imposed on <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s government in 1985 In the past two years, the chairman of <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>'s state petroleum company has met with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil company officials in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and other West European cities, a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> oil company official said Wednesday. He said the two sides are discussing a possible return of the Americans under terms of an agreement signed a few months after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> imposed the embargo on <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> in 1986. The agreement on July 1, 1986, froze <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> oil company assets and allowed the Libyans to work their oil fields, the Western source said, with <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> assuming all costs but also taking all the income. Before the embargo, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> got 51 percent of the oil produced by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies. The agreement provides for the same split if the embargo is lifted and the source said of the Americans: `` They will return.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies said to be involved are <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Oasis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> and a consortium of <ORGANIZATION> Conoco </ORGANIZATION>, Marathon and <PERSON> Amerada </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON>. The 1986 agreement expires June 30, 1989, but if the Americans are not back by then an extension probably will be arrianged because both sides are eager to do business again, the source said. An official of the state oil company said: `` We are waiting to see what happens at the start of next year,'' and expressed a common Libyan opinion that restrictions might be relaxed when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> leaves office. All those who commented did so on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> imposed the sanctions in January 1986 because of <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s alleged support of terrorism, and forbade Americaans to work in <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. The work ban has been costly for <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. The state oil company official said it replaced the departing American workers by advertising around the world for highly skilled managers and technicians. He said the places were filled by Britons, Canadians, Swedes, Indians and French workers, but at a high cost. About 400 Americans worked in the Libyan oil industry before the embargo, he said. Spare parts for American equipment also had to be obtained elsewhere at higher prices. Lower world prices have caused <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>'s oil revenue to decline from $ 22 billion in 1980 to $ 6 billion in 1986.
