<HEAD>New Yorker Set to Stalk Gators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> OKEECHOBEE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> -LRB- A -RRB- _ Streetwise New Yorker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON> knows more about urban sharks than swamp alligators, but that's about to change as he takes to the waters of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okeechobee </LOCATION> on Thursday in the first statewide gator hunt in 26 years. `` This guy does n't know an airboat from an air hose,'' said professional gator-hunter <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON>, who will serve as <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON>'s guide `` I'm here to make sure we get the gators, not vice versa.'' Beginning at sundown Thursday, the two men will head out onto the lake as the most unusual and celebrated of the 238 participants in the gator hunt, which was organized in response to a growing alligator population estimated at 1 million. Former Ivy Leaguer <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON>, 25, acknowledged with a tip of his <ORGANIZATION> Mets </ORGANIZATION>' baseball cap that he is enjoying his well-publicized role as the only Northerner among the hunters. `` They all think I'm a bit strange,'' said <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON>, who left his loft apartment in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> on Tuesday. `` You know, the city boy out in the country sort of thing. I'm just taking it all in.'' He has caught the attention of the major television networks and nearly every large newspaper in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Last week, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> environmental officials gave <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON> a T-shirt decorated with a sunglasses-wearing alligator climbing out of a city sewer, in jest of the tales of freed pet alligators roaming beneath the streets. `` It's all been an adventure in itself. I never thought I'd be a newsmaker,'' he said. `` But I like doing odd things, so I guess it just comes with the territory.'' <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON>, a free-lance writer and aspiring race-car driver, said he contacted <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> game officials in May after reading about the hunt in a magazine. <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bart </PERSON> <PERSON> McBeth </PERSON> of Sulphur, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, were the only two out-of-state residents randomly selected from about 5,000 applications to participate in the monthlong season. <PERSON> McBeth </PERSON> could not be reached by telephone Wednesday to confirm he will join the hunt. <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON>, who will be allowed to take 15 gators with his permit, said he selected <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON>, 51, as a guide after learning the danger in gator hunting. `` I've never hunted anything except a bird I shot with a BB gun as a kid,'' said <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON>, who has practiced on a shooting range, however, and will take his practice gun with him on the hunt. <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON> left <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 after one year of classes and is working on a bachelor's degree at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Between schools, he devoted himself to auto racing. In 1985, the last time he was in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, he crashed his Formula Ford race car at a track. He spent the next year racing in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and trying to develop a new British-Italian Formula 3 car. Later, back in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, he began helicopter lessons. On Wednesday, he got some ideas of what he can expect to earn on his adventure into the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION>. On a white legal pad, <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> rapidly tallied some figures: take 15 gators, subtract money for <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON>'s $ 1,000 out-of-state permit and $ 75 each for processing and other expenses, and it leaves about $ 4,000 in potential profits from the sale of the carcasses. <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON> thought for a moment and proposed an even split. A handshake consummated the deal.
