<HEAD>Mandela Moved To Private Clinic, Possibly Setting Stage For
Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jailed black nationalist <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> has been moved from a hospital to a private clinic while he recuperates from tuberculosis, the government said Thursday. The move sets the stage for a possible release from government custody. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, 70, was transferred on Aug. 12 from <LOCATION> Pollsmoor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION>, to nearby <LOCATION> Tygerberg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where he was diagnosed with the disease. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, leader of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, has been in prison for 26 years. He has been making a speedy recovery from his illness, his doctors have said, and was moved late Wednesday night to the <ORGANIZATION> Constantiaberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, a spokesman for the prison service, <PERSON> Danie </PERSON> <PERSON> Immelman </PERSON>, told the independent <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s condition has improved to such an extent that his further treatment in the <LOCATION> Tygerberg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> was no longer necessary,'' <PERSON> Immelman </PERSON> was quoted as saying. The spokesman gave no indication of how long would be in the clinic or what the conditions of his stay would be like. The move appears to confirm widespread speculation that <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> would be placed in a private clinic and gradually reintroduced to the South African public before the government decides whether to release him outright. Under this widely accepted scenario, <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> is expected to have access to a greater number of visitors and possibly even allowed to conduct media interviews. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s full recuperation is likely to at least several weeks and after that period, the government can then choose whether to send him back to prison or grant him freedom. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, in a major speech two weeks ago, said he was seriously considering releasing <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, the country's best-known black leader <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> has been jailed since 1962 and is serving a life sentence for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-led government. His continued imprisonment has the government in a difficult bind. If <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> releases <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, the president risks an enormous white backlash and the possibility of reactivating militant black opposition that has been largely suppressed under the 26-month-old state of emergency. If <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> keeps <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> in prison, there could be widespread black unrest if the country's preeminent black leader dies in prison. Nationwide municipal elections are set for Oct. 26, further complicating <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s dilemma. The government is engaged in a massive campaign to encourage blacks to vote in municipal township elections, but it also faces a growing threat from conservative whites. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s release would likely encourage black voters to go to the polls, but could harm <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s national party in the separate white local elections. The different race groups vote in separate local elections but the nation's black majority has no vote in national affairs. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has offered since 1985 to release <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> if he will renounce violence. However, <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> has said that the government's 1960 decision to ban the then-peaceful <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> left him no choice but to fight <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> has said he will disavow violence only if the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> is not longer banned, apartheid is dismantled and blacks are given a voice in national affairs.
