<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION> signed a `` joint commitment'' Wednesday to cut by half thousands of expensive grievance appeals, arbitrations and employment discrimination complaints annually. The non-binding agreement to improve the labor-management climate is the first ever signed by the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> with a union representing its employees. According to <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> records, 19,543 grievances were appealed beyond the local level by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION> union in the 12 months ending Aug. 1, and 10,766 individual disputes were taken to arbitration. In addition, members of the union filed 2,128 complaints of age, sex or race discrimination against the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> with the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The two-page accord said a joint employee involvement process by the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the 310,000-member union has improved labor-management relations over the past five years. However, it added that `` tension and antagonism remain at an intolerable level in many work locations ... and the number of grievances filed and arbitrations conducted is unacceptable.'' The accord was worked out after Postmaster General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> became the first person ever holding that post to address a postal union convention when he spoke to the Letter Carriers last month in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION> `` These processes ... break down the old ` them' and ` us' attitudes and promote a positive spirit of cooperation,'' he said `` In short they save money for both sides, improve productivity -LRB- and -RRB- reduce workplace stress.'' Postal Service officials said the cooperation agreement does not alter any terms of a 40-month labor contract signed last summer.
