<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s allies in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> approved free-trade legislation Wednesday to eliminate economic barriers with <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But members of the opposition-dominated <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> say they will stall the bill. With both sides waving <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> flags and the opposition singing the national anthem, the Commons voted 177-64 for the agreement signed in January by <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The Progressive Conservatives, with 207 of the 282 seats in the Commons, easily out-voted the combined opposition and sent the bill to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The Liberals and New Democrats, who call the trade deal a sellout of Canadian sovereignty, interrupted the final vote by singing `` O <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>.'' During two raucous votes on opposition amendments, Speaker <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> admonished members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> to settle down and asked New Democrats and Conservatives alike to put down their Canadian flags and pins. But the bill, which would amend 27 federal statutes to make <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s border more open to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> goods and services, faces a rough road ahead. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> has suggested strongly that he will call a federal election this fall before the scheduled Jan. 1 launch of the trade treaty. And the Liberal majority in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has promised to stall the legislation until the issue is decided one way or another in an election. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> legislation on the treaty has been approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> and is expected to pass the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> later this month. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s deputy chief trade negotiator over the two years of talks with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said the agreement will not be in effect until the deal gets through the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the prime minister actually exchanges a letter of ratification with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> president. `` We're saving the champagne for the ratification,'' said <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>. Public opinion surveys indicate Canadians are almost equally divided on the merits of the agreement but generally agree on thing _ the issue is confusing. Under the trade agreement, both countries would begin phasing out border taxes, quotas, standards and other regulations that stop or discourge trade. Future disputes could be referred to five-member panels of trade experts from both countries for settlement. The Canadian government has touted the deal as a boon for business and jobs as well as cutting the $ 2 billion a year in tariffs that Canadian businesses and consumers have to pay on imports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The opposition says other Canadian jobs will be lost as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business moves into the Canadian market. Consumers will only see a fraction of the value of the tariff cuts, they say. The agreement was reached last fall after 18 months of talks between the two nations.
