<HEAD>Court Upholds Symphony's Cancellation of Vanessa Redgrave Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> did not violate the civil rights of actress <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON> <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON> when it canceled her performances following threats by protesters, a federal appeals court ruled Wednesday. The full <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 1st </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled by a 3-2 vote that the cancellation did not violate the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Civil Rights Act. It was an unusual reversal of an earlier finding by a three-member panel of the appellate court. Wednesday's decision reinstated an award to compensate Ms. <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON> $ 12,000 she would have earned in a Broadway role she lost during the suit against the symphony. However, expenses the actress would have incurred while appearing in the play will be subtracted from the award. Orchestra attorney <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said symphony officials were relieved with the ruling. `` I think they're also happy that the case is probably over now and they can go back to doing what they're best at _ making music,'' he said. Attorneys for Ms. <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON>, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kornstein </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Wexler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, were not in their offices and did not return calls Wednesday evening. Ms. <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON> was hired by the symphony in 1982 to narrate six performances of <PERSON> Stravinsky </PERSON>'s `` Oedipus Rex'' at <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tanglewood </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Carnegie Hall. But the contract was canceled after the symphony received letters and telephone calls indicating there would be picketing and other protests because of Ms. <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON>'s support of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. In November 1984, a federal jury ruled the symphony had breached its contract with Ms. <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON> and awarded her the $ 27,500 she was to have received for the performances plus $ 100,000 in compensatory damages for work the actress said she lost because of the action. In February 1985, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeton </PERSON> threw out the $ 100,000 award and ruled the symphony had not violated her civil rights. Last October, a three-member panel of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 1st </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> restored $ 12,000 of that award as compensation for the lost role. The three-member panel also found the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Civil Rights Act had been violated. Attorneys for the symphony, arguing that <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> law allowed them to cancel performances because of concerns that threatened disruptions would mar the artistic integrity of the performances, asked for a rehearing before the full court. Wednesday's ruling by the full court, effectively reversing the earlier finding, was unusual, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. `` This is a very, very rare thing,'' he said. `` The 1st Circuit very seldom reverses themselves.''
