<HEAD>Delta Crash Revives Memories Of Earlier Delta Accident For
Rescuers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th, `Flight 191...' to include comment
from hospital worker.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the passengers who survived the crash of a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet on Wednesday may owe their lives to another crash three years ago, rescuers said. `` Last time we did n't know what to expect. This time we're a little more organized,'' said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Cartier </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> volunteer. `` Last time'' was the crash of <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> Flight 191, a <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> L-1011, on the other side of <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> three years ago in which 137 people died. `` Flight 191 definitely gave us more experience,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Sympson </PERSON>, paramedic supervisor for the airport police and fire department. `` When we got here, it was click, click, click.'' `` There was a lot of preparation done because of the last one,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Muncy </PERSON>, a lab technician at the 314-bed Harris Methodist H.E.B. Hospital, where many of the injured were taken. `` Everyone was right in place. There was no wasted motion. We knew just what to do.'' <PERSON> Sympson </PERSON> arrived aboard one of the first three emergency vehicles at the crash scene just three minutes after the 9:03 a.m. accident at the airport's west end. Dozens of fire trucks, helicopters and police vehicles converged on the prairie southwest of the main airport tower, and within 10 minutes some of the first victims were being transported to hospitals, <PERSON> Sympson </PERSON> said. `` When we got to the plane, the majority of the survivors were on the grass, away from the plane,'' <PERSON> Sympson </PERSON> said. A van driver, <PERSON> Eusebio </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON>, said he was several hundred yards away when the plane cracked open and a column of flame erupted from the tail area. <PERSON> Sympson </PERSON> and others in the first wave of rescuers concentrated on establishing a triage area where survivors could be evaluated and the most seriously injured expedited to hospitals. The paramedics said all they were told only that the plane was a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727. It was n't until thick, black smoke cleared 15 or 20 minutes later that they discovered they were working on another <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> plane. When paramedic <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON> arrived on the scene, `` all I heard was screaming from the people on the ground.'' `` Some of them -LRB- the survivors -RRB- were in severe shock, but some of them were joking, trying to I guess make the situation easier,'' <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON> said. `` One guy laughed and said, ` Boy, I'm not going to take an airplane home.' Ca n't really blame him at that point.'' <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, an airport Department of Public Safety officer, was off duty when he heard about the crash on the news and came in to work about 9:40 a.m. `` I just helped pull bodies out _ about nine,'' said <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>. `` They were charred. Some of them were in seats. Some of them were n't in seats. Some had belts on we had to take off. `` The ones that I pulled out were in the back of the plane,'' he said. <PERSON> Sympson </PERSON> said this crash was similar to the one three years ago. `` There was not a big difference,'' <PERSON> Sympson </PERSON> said. `` There was fire, smoke and you did n't know what you were going to find. I'm simply amazed there were this many survivors. Paramedic <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Seadore </PERSON> said he was the first paramedic to arrive at both crashes. `` I tell you I had some flashbacks,'' <PERSON> Seadore </PERSON> said of Wednesday's disaster. One result of the 1985 crash was a greater emphasis on helping rescuers cope with what they saw and had to do when they arrived to help Wednesday. <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, still wearing his silver flame-proof coveralls and hard hat, said those who helped pull victims from the plane were sent to a stress center where they received tetanus shots. Then they were taken to a stress clinic for counseling. `` Anyone who pulled out bodies went through that,'' he said. `` You never get used to it. But you got a job to do, and you just go ahead and do it.'' Hundreds of people were on hand at the crash site within an hour after the accident. Within two hours, volunteers from charitable agencies had arrived to provide food and beverages to workers in what was expected to be a day-long effort. `` We work with relatives and victims, ensuring they've got nurses, preachers to talk to, and we meet their transportation needs by taking them to the hospitals and hotels,'' <PERSON> Cartier </PERSON> said.
