<HEAD>Former Charleston Mayor Testifies Before Bar Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Mayor <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>, battling to save his law license after pleading guilty to drug charges, admitted to a Bar panel Wednesday that he took no action while prosecutor against two men who sold him drugs. <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>, who turned 43 on Wednesday, testified for about 25 minutes before a subcommittee of the state Bar's <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. It is considering whether sanctions should be imposed, up to revocation of <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>'s law license, because of his guilty pleas. <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> pleaded guilty to six misdemeanor federal charges of possession of cocaine and resigned as mayor as part of the plea agreement. He was released from federal prison on July 20 after serving 5 -LCB- months. Ethics panel chairman <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Recht </PERSON> said the central issue at the hearing is whether a public official should be treated differently in a disciplinary matter from lawyers in private practice. <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>'s side said he should not and asked for leniency. But Bar disciplinary counsel <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Marden </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> used his position to shield those supplying drugs. Under cross-examination, <PERSON> Marden </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>, who admitted using drugs while <LOCATION> Kanawha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutor, whether he tried to bring charges against two men who supplied drugs to him and were convicted by federal prosecutors. `` I took no steps to prosecute either or advise anybody,'' <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Kanawha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Prosecutor <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, both top assistants to <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> when he was prosecutor, said <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> showed no leniency toward drug dealers. But <PERSON> King </PERSON> said he could not recall <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> participating in any drug prosecutions. The state Bar rested its case against <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> without calling a witness. On the stand, <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> took full blame for his actions and said he was sorry for what had happened. `` I have no excuses and I offer none,'' said <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>, who has been practicing law since his release from prison. `` I obviously knew what I was doing was wrong at the time I was doing it.'' But <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> said he believes that he has paid and pays daily for his actions. He asked the panel to allow him to maintain his law license so he can make restitution to the community for his misbehavior. <PERSON> Recht </PERSON> said the panel should render a decision sometime in October. Its recommendation goes to the full <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which makes its final report to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The court can then agree to the recommendation, modify or reject it. Former <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> Police Chief <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckalew </PERSON>, called on behalf of the <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>, testified Wednesday that <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> never attempted to interfere with his agency. <PERSON> Buckalew </PERSON> said his drug officers generally worked under federal supervision and he had little control over them anyway. But he did say that in 1985 he was aware that <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> was being investigated concerning drug matters. `` Did <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> try to curtail drug enforcement?'' asked <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>'s attorney. `` No, he did not,'' replied <PERSON> Buckalew </PERSON>, police chief from 1983 to 1985. On cross-examination, <PERSON> Marden </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Buckalew </PERSON> whether <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> had ever lied to him. `` Yes, he did,'' <PERSON> Buckalew </PERSON> said. `` He was not truthful as to his plea of guilty to cocaine use. He indicated to me he was not using it.''
