<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Plans for the <ORGANIZATION> Ronald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> hit a snag Wednesday when questions were raised at an environmental hearing about the project's effects on air quality, plant life and traffic congestion. The Ventura County Environmental Report Review recessed the hearing for a week to get more information. At next week's meeting, the committee could either approve the library project, delay a decision again or decide that an Environmental Impact Report is needed. The <ORGANIZATION> Ronald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> wants to build the library on a 100-acre site which lies partly within a greenbelt area that is protected from large-scale development by a decade-old, non-binding agreement among the communities of <LOCATION> Moorpark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Simi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thousand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>. The library, scheduled for completion in 1991, would house President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s White House papers and would contain museum exhibits about his administration. Like the eight existing presidential libraries, it would be built with private funds and then operated by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, who represents the county <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pollution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> on the seven-member committee, asked for the delay, saying the district had found the project inconsistent with county air quality standards. `` It would bring in a lot of additional traffic that is not projected,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. The foundation estimates that the library would attract 350,000 visitors a year. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, a private environmental group in <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said, however, it believed the number of visitors per year could exceed 425,000. `` I think I would have to come down against it'' if the matter were voted on without further investigation, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> told the committee. Other members of the committee said they needed more information on traffic density and the effect on vegetation before making a decision. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Worthley </PERSON>, regional manager of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> and Game, wrote to county officials on May 12 that an undisclosed number of specimens of three `` sensitive plant species'' would be harmed or destroyed by construction. He suggested a detailed site survey `` at the appropriate time of year when these plants can be readily identified and that the project be redesigned to avoid these areas as much as possible.'' <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gatch </PERSON>, director of planning and community development for Thousand Oaks, said in a letter written Tuesday that part of the public road over which traffic would travel to reach the library site `` remains a two-lane roadway operating at a level of service beyond its current capacity.'' Others at the hearing said they understood this section was to be widened before the scheduled 1991 opening of the library. If the project is approved by the committee, critics would have 10 days in which to appeal. The committee would hear the appeal in another 30 days. If an Environmental Impact Report is required, it could take a year or more. The foundation, which hopes to break ground for the library this fall, would have the right to appeal any decision to order an Environmental Impact Report.
