 Top aides to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> denied Wednesday that they told <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> not to campaign in several states as tension between the two Democrats increased. Sources close to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said the former presidential candidate was angered at being told to avoid campaigning in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. The sources said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> officials had determined <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> could hurt the ticket among traditionally Democratic blue collar voters in some states who supported <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1980 and 1984. `` I am aware of no list of states provided to him, of states he should not or would not or we prefer he not go into,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign manager <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON>. But one aide to the Democratic nominee, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the campaign conducted polling in every state for favorable and unfavorable opinions on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> `` to see how well he can do in the fall in attracting swing voters as well as blacks.'' The results found that in some of the primary states he won, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had high negatives among those swing voters. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is making a strong bid to woo those so-called <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> <PERSON> Democrats </PERSON> back to their former allegiance to Democratic presidential candidates. In <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> State Rep. <PERSON> Roscoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has invited him and other key supporters to a meeting Thursday in <LOCATI