<HEAD>Delta Accident Comes As Lawsuit Over Flight 191 Responsibility
Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Delta Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN-TORRES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three years after a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> jet crashed on takeoff in a severe thunderstorm at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, a federal court battle continues over responsibility for the accident. On Aug. 2, 1985, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> Flight 191 crashed and burned, killing 137 people and injuring 25 others. In Wednesday's crash of Flight 1141 on takeoff in cloudless skies for <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, 13 people were killed and 94 survived. The plane went down at the opposite end of the airport from the 1985 crash. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> investigators ruled in July 1986 that the Delta 191 crash occurred when the L-1101 flew into a microburst containing several wind shears. The strong, abrupt downward shifts in wind direction at the south end of the airport smashed the jet into the ground. Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> and the government are continuing a 6-month-old federal trial in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> to determine responsibility. Earlier this month, testimony was postponed until October while a federal judge tries to clear other cases. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, which initially admitted some responsibility for the crash, claims government air traffic controllers and weather forecasters failed to warn the flight crew of the storm. The trial involving <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, its insurers and the widow of the pilot is the first in which a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline has gone to court against the government to seek damages. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> officials claim the government should bear responsibility for the crash and pay all or part of more than $ 90 million in death, injury and damage claims the airline already has paid. More than 90 lawsuits seeking more than $ 200 million dollars were filed by victims' relatives. Lawyers for the government contend the flight crew should have been able to avoid the crash. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> faulted crew training for handling wind shears and the lack of `` definitive'' weather information as contributing factors in the accident. But the Atlanta-based airline maintains the board's findings were `` incomplete, inaccurate and most painfully flawed.'' Officials said the crew operated the craft in accordance with <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> procedures and regulations.
