<HEAD>Dirty Air Prompts Emergency Measures; At Least 75 People
Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Wednesday banned half the city's taxis and private autos from the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> area and ordered factories to slow down to reduce a smog cloud that sent at least 75 people to the hospital. The government Program for Pollution Control said the emergency measures are to remain in effect Thursday. `` There is no wind and we have a high nitrogen dioxide content in the atmosphere,'' said anti-pollution agency spokesman <PERSON> Dimitris </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadjidakis </PERSON>. The agency said levels of nitrogen dioxide, a poisonous reddish-brown gas formed from auto exhaust, reached 561 micrograms per cubic meter Wednesday in parts of central <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, more than twice the danger level of 200 micrograms. A reading of 500 or more calls for emergency measures. The state-run <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Help </ORGANIZATION> said 55 people suffering from pollution-caused heart and respiratory problems were treated at hospital outpatient clincs in the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> area on Wednesday. Twenty others were hospitalized after fainting on the capital's streets. A private pollution monitoring organization, the <ORGANIZATION> Panhellenic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, gave a higher figure of 309 for the number of people requiring hospital treatment. Half the city's 730,000 private cars and 15,000 taxis were banned from a 115-square mile area around the city center while <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>' 120 biggest factories were told to reduce output by 30 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. Only vehicles with licence plates ending in odd numbers were allowed in the area. Both