<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> called for support from opposition leaders on Wednesday after violent protests followed his nomination as the only candidate in an October presidential referendum. Authorities said hundreds were arrested during widespread rioting Tuesday and three people were killed, including two teen-age boys, as residents threw open their windows and banged pots and pans in defiance. Rioting in the streets broke out after the military junta nominated <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who took part in the selection process, to be the sole nominee in an October presidential referendum. In a nationally broadcast address Wednesday night, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> made a rare appeal for opposition backing. In previous addresses, he has dismissed opponents as `` traitors,'' `` rats,'' `` highwaymen'' and `` cowards.'' `` Our democracy needs the collaboration of all Chileans,'' he said. `` I call today on my compatriots, supporters and opponents, to assume this noble task. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> needs you.'' The remarks followed huge demonstratons by thousands of people in the capital and elsewhere. In <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> alone, 846 protesters were arrested during the day-long street demonstrations and clashes, a report from the national police said. It gave no precise figure for arrests outside the capital, although scores were reported arrested in protests in most other cities. Many of those arrested were being released Wednesday after an identity check, some without being charged and others cited to appear before city judges. The national police said the dead included two boys, age 14 and 15, and an adult. It said 21 people were injured in the rioting. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who commands the army, has led the military government that has governed <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> since September 1973, when the elected government of Marxist President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> was overthrown in a bloody coup by the armed forces. <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> died in the coup. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> was picked in a meeting with the chiefs of the navy, air force and national police to be the sole candidate in an Oct. 5 presidential referendum. If a majority vote in his favor, he will assume a new eight-year term on March 11. If voters reject him, he remains in power until 1990 when an open presidential election is to be held in conjuction with elections for a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The nomination came despite appeals by the local Roman Catholic church and several moderate political organizations for a candidate who would have the backing of both the government and opposition. It also ended speculation that the other commanders, who had publicly expressed support for a civilian nominee, would insist that <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> give up his army commandership in return for the candidacy. The formal nomination declaration refers repeatedly to <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> as army leader and the army commander pointedly made his acceptance speech in military uniform. He can legally remain army leader if he wins the referendum and remains president. Opposition leaders, meanwhile, said that <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s nomination will backfire. ` This confrontational decision directly compromises the armed forces, who will suffer from his defeat in the plebescite,'' <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, leader of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday of <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s selection. The opposition cites several opinion polls that give a 2-1 advantage to <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> opponents in the ballot. Government-contracted polls give him a slight edge in the vote. Speaking to foreign reporters, <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s army commandership `` acts as a kind of shield, and exerts moral pressure on his institution.'' `` Pinochet is too attached to power, and I do n't believe he is willing to give up any of his priveleges,'' he said. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> described `` as generally peaceful'' Tuesday's anti-government protests, in which thousands of people participated But he said he expected that the incidents of violence would be politically exploited by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s administration Interior Minister <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> issued a declaration Wednesday that blamed the violence on the political opposition. `` Once again, extremist groups have sewed death and fear. Those responsible for these acts are clearly identified with the -LRB- supports of a -RRB- vote of ` no.' Christian Democrat vice-president <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON> said, however, `` The only violence occurred where there was police repression.'' Riot police squads had broken the demonstrations with tear gas and water cannon. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> described one of Tuesday's falities, that of a 15-year-old boy, as `` one more youth added to the victims of the dictatorship.'' The boy was participating in a pot-banging protest when he was shot twice in the chest by gunmen in a passing car. A 1980 Constitution crafted by the <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> government calls for a phased return to democracy, including a resumption of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1990. However, about a third of the <ORGANIZATION> senate </ORGANIZATION> would government appointees and high-ranking military officials. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> also A declaration signed by leaders of a 16-party opposition coalition Wednesday reaffirmed their plans to campaign for a vote of `` no'' in the referendum and, if they win, to negotiate with the armed forces for constitutional changes.
