<HEAD>Washington State Teachers Enthusiastic Over Reform Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-School Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For years, <PERSON> Reggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON> and fellow teachers at <ORGANIZATION> Moses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> had looked for ways to break the traditional public school mold and give students the special attention denied them in a rigid system. This year, <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON> and the others will get a chance to experiment with reform, freed of state requirements under a pilot program called `` Schools for the 21st Century'' created this year by the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>. He is among several hundred teachers in 21 school districts involved in a bold plan aimed at giving the state `` a world class education system by the 21st century,'' in the words of Gov. <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>. Backed by $ 2.1 million in state money to pay teachers for extra time spent planning, the program will allow the teachers to shake up their classrooms rather than their bosses and the school boards who've been dictating what to do. `` Now, with the flexibility of the 21st century program, we can experiment. It gives us a way to create, to do something different,'' said <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON>, who teaches Spanish and social studies in <LOCATION> Moses </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, a central <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> city about 230 miles east of <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON> says his first order of business is to expand his homework hotline, a program in which high school students can call peers for help with homework. `` We're starting a guest speaker program. We're also starting a telephone counseling service where students can call anonymously and get referred to places where they can get help for drug addiction or whatever,'' <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON>'s excitement can also be found at <LOCATION> Moses </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Larson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. There, teachers are reorganizing curricula and classrooms for the 300 pupils, many of whom are from low-income families and lag in achievement. `` Basically, what the teachers are doing is creating opportunities to enrich these kids, to enrich their minds,'' said <PERSON> P.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON>, a district official working with the teachers on alternative education plans. For example, the teachers have decided to keep <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> Heights open until 6 p.m. each day, giving latchkey kids and others a way to profit from free time. `` The kids can use the school computers. They can work on their homework in a quiet, supervised setting. There will be storytime, organized recreation, arts and crafts,'' <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think I've ever seen our teachers this excited or this enthusiastic,'' said <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> superintendent <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Edlund </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
