^For Release Sunday, Sept 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Moves to Take Over Troubled Urban District</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With BC-School Reform
^By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Backed by a broad new law, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> is trying to seize control of a major urban school district it considers to be educationally bankrupt. State officials say schools in <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>'s second largest city, are so crippled by political patronage that local leaders can not make desperately needed improvements. Symptomatic, they say, are curricula on Afro-American history that end with the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration. City officials disagree and are trying to block the takeover. <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is providing the first test of a law enacted in January giving <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> power to take over chronically troubled schools. <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> have laws of varying strength allowing state takeovers of failing school districts, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Laws in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> let the state eliminate deficient districts, and an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> law allows the state to revoke a district's charter. A <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law allows financial penalties in the form of reduced state aid. If <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> wins, it can abolish the local board of education, fire administrators and appoint a state superintendent to operate the district of 32,000 students for five years. `` When schools fail, it's adults who failed, and adults should pay the price,'' Gov. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> said when he signed the law. <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> officials say their city suffers from the poverty and crime typical of urban districts. They contend that to single out <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> for state takeover is unfair when efforts are being made to reverse the decay from years of political intrusion under former administrations. The state launched the takeover in May after almost three years of investigation and monitoring in the district. `` I do n't think they were looking for anything right. They were on a mission to point up what was wrong,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Massa </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>. Takeover hearings before an administrative law judge are expected to last into January. The earliest the state could take control is next May, but appeals by the district could further delay action. State investigators said they found financial irregularities, questionable payroll and personnel practices and incompetent management. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, the state's lead investigator, said district employees are routinely rewarded or demoted based on which mayoral candidate they backed in the most recent election. They also cited low test scores and high truancy rates. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> students registered the third lowest passing rate in the state on a mandatory statewide ninth-grade test. Eleven other <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> districts, including <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, are in the third and final stage of state monitoring that precedes a takeover. Six of the districts are working with the state to make improvements, and officials hope the <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> action sends a signal that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> is ready to act again if a district fails to make the grade.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept 4</NOTE>
