<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview ADV00   08-31 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, ADV00,0524</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Betrayed''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> is unique among world-class filmmakers. He alone has made a career of polemics on such issues as military dictatorships -LRB- `` Z'' -RRB- and American meddling abroad -LRB- `` Missing'' -RRB-. His films have swayed world opinion while gripping audiences with his documentary-style drama. Because no one else attacks social ills on a regular basis, it is regrettable that he stumbles with `` Betrayed.'' The film begins with a Costa-Gavras imprint: a graphic depiction of heart-pounding violence. Over the titles, an acerbic radio talk-show host spouts insults at his favorite targets: rock music, fat women and bigots. As he leaves the studio, he is followed by another car, then is gunned down in a parking structure by unseen assailants. The episode, obviously inspired by the murder of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> broadcaster <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Berg </PERSON>, establishes the timeliness of `` Betrayed.'' But this early promise later dissipates in an illogical and overstated melodrama. A dedicated <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent, Debra Winger, unwillingly accepts the assignment of trying to infiltrate a Midwestern hate group suspected of the broadcaster's murder. Posing as a harvester machine driver, she quickly ingratiates herself to a good ol' boy charmer, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON>. With his overalls, homespun manner and two small motherless children, he seems as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> as a Big Mac. The romance grows, and marriage is proposed. But <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON> has a challenge for his wife-to-be: He wants her not only to approve of his secret paramiliatry society but to participate in its robberies and murders. An intriguing situation, but it is destroyed by overkill. Winger's first trial is taking part in a midnight `` game'' in which a young black is set loose in a thicket with a gun and 10 bullets and hunted down by dogs and heavily armed farmers. Even `` Rambo'' fans would have trouble buying this one. Following the trend of recent films, Winger's <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> superiors are portrayed as incompetents. They allow her to remain in a life-threatening situation with no backup or support. They do n't even follow her and <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON> when the pair embark on an assassination trip Nor is there concern when Winger herself commits a crime, shooting a guard during a bank robbery. The actors strive for credibility, but the <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Esterhaz </PERSON> script and <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON>' overzealous direction defeat them. Debra Winger's intensity helps keep her character alive <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON> proved his talent for portraying evil in `` Platoon,'' but he has no chance here to reconcile the normal-seeming farmer and the hate-warped psycho. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> production is rated R for language and violence. Running time: 127 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> rating definitions: G _ General audiences. All ages admitted. PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be suitable for children. PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children. R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian. X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age restrictions.
</TEXT>
