<SECOND>BC-JC Penney-Stock,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.C. Penney Creates $700 Million Employee Stock Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has borrowed $ 700 million to create a leveraged employee stock ownership plan in conjunction with an expanded stock buyback program, the retailing company announced Tuesday. The so-called LESOP, a tax-qualified employee benefit trust that invests in the sponsoring company's securities, will replace <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION>'s existing employee savings and profit-sharing retirement plan. <PERSON> Penney </PERSON> employees already own 15 percent of the company's 132 million common shares outstanding through their existing retirement plan. The LESOP is using the proceeds of the $ 700 million loan to purchase a new issue of convertible preferred stock from the company, officials said. The preferred stock is convertible into about 11.8 million shares of the company's common stock, about 9 percent of the currently outstanding common shares. <PERSON> Penney </PERSON> will use the $ 700 million it gets from the employee trust to buy back 15 million common shares from the public. Therefore, the employees will end up controlling 31.6 million common shares, or about 24.5 percent of the common shares that ultimately will be outstanding. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>'s chairman, said the plan would help boost shareholder value. `` We see these steps as strengthening the interests of our major constituencies: our investors, our consumers and our associates -LRB- employees -RRB-.'' `` It wo n't really have an effect on our day-to-day operation,'' said company spokesman <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON>. `` As far as long term, it should boost our earnings per share, reduce costs, and increase our cash flow.'' Such employee stock ownership plans commonly have been implemented by corporations anxious to place a large block of their shares into friendly hands, thus helping thwart potential raids. <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>'s plan is the largest such LESOP yet created, according to some reports. <PERSON> Penney </PERSON> said it would redirect its annual contribution from the savings plan to the LESOP. Last year, those contributions were $ 50 million. <PERSON> Penney </PERSON> stock rose $ 1.87 -LCB- a share to $ 48.12 -LCB- Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
