<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's chief economic forecasting gauge suffered the steepest drop in eight months in July, but few analysts expect a substantial slackening in growth anytime soon. The 0.8 percent decline reported Tuesday in the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Index of Leading Economic Indicators was the biggest since last November, when the index dropped 1.0 percent in the aftermath of the October stock market crash. But economists noted that the index posted an exceptionally strong increase in June and cautioned against reading too much into a one-month downturn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The biggest drop in defense orders in more than four years contributed to a sharp decline in July orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods, the government says. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that orders for both durable and non-durable goods fell 3.5 percent to $ 220.2 billion last month. It was the worst drop since January 1987, when orders fell 3.6 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The drought helped lift prices farmers got for raw products in August by 2.1 percent from July, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. The report released Tuesday said August prices averaged 13 percent higher than a year earlier. The report also included revised figures showing the index rose only 2.9 percent in July, compared with the preliminary reading of 3.6 percent announced a month ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Contracting for new construction fell 5 percent in July after spurting higher the previous two months, according to a new report. The July decline was concentrated in the public works sector, the F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. It said construction activity has been drifting downward since last fall. `` Expectations for a lasting turn-around, which were none too high before the latest round of credit restraint, have just been lowered,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>, chief economist of F.W. Dodge, said in a statement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has stopped <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> from firing 4,000 employees but has allowed the financially-strapped carrier to go ahead with service cutbacks to 14 cities as planned. `` Massive layoffs are not, and shall never be business as usual,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Barrington </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said in a 50-page opinion. `` The Railway Labor Act requires Eastern to bargain with its unions before taking unilateral action to eliminate 12 percent of its workforce.'' Eastern President <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> called the decision `` gravely wrong'' and said the carrier would file an emergency appeal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The flight attendants union says <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> is using <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> as his personal cash cow to the detriment of the airline and public safety. The union asked Tuesday that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> block <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s plan to take <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> private and to freeze <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> assets while it investigates his fitness to continue managing the airline. Through spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> called <ORGANIZATION> IFFA </ORGANIZATION>'s allegations `` spurious, malicious and erroneous'' and designed `` to embarrass the airline.''
