<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest organization of certified public accountants has voted to end its 82-year-old ban on accepting certain fees and commissions, a move officials said would allow CPAs to become more competitive. The ruling council of the 272,000-member <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Certified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pubic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accountants </ORGANIZATION>, under pressure from the government, voted 191-5 Tuesday to drop bans against accepting compensation for financial planning that CPAs have long said invite conflicts of interest. The institute had been under pressure by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to allow commissions for non-audit work performed by accountants.
