<FIRST>r f PM-EconomyRdp     08-31 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Indicators Decline; Financial Markets Quiet</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock, bond and currency markets showed little reaction after the government reported a 0.8 percent drop in its main indicator of the economy's strength, the biggest decline since after the crash of the stock market. Tuesday's report actually comforted some economists and investors who feared the economy was expanding too rapidly, raising the danger of higher inflation, higher interest rates and eventually a recession. The government also said Tuesday that factory orders fell 3.5 percent in July, the biggest monthly drop since January 1987. But economists said the decline had little significance because it was caused mainly by a swing in the volatile category of defense orders. `` For those people who were worried that we were in for a major acceleration of inflation, these numbers probably calm some nerves,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, economic forecasting firm. Stock prices generally rose Tuesday in a slow session, although the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 3.20 points to 2,038.23 after a 24-point gain on Monday. The dollar fell Tuesday against most major currencies, while bond prices finished slightly higher. The yield of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-year bond, which falls when the market strengthens, dipped to 9.32 percent from 9.33 percent late Monday <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON> said the reports should help encourage the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to hold off on any further tightening moves unless new evidence of inflation surfaces. The decline in the leading indicators was the biggest since last November, when the index dropped 1.0 percent in the aftermath of the October stock market crash. Economists noted the index posted an exceptionally strong increase in June and cautioned against reading too much into a one-month downturn. `` Despite the declines, we're not going to have any slowing in the imminent future,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturing, which languished earlier in the decade because of the strong dollar, has rebounded. The weaker dollar has fueled a resurgence in sales of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> goods overseas and businesses have responded by spending more to upgrade and replace plant and equipment. But demand for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods has been so strong that some analysts are concerned that factory capacity will be strained, pushing prices higher. Factory orders, excluding the defense category, were down 0.7 percent in July following a healthy 2.9 percent gain in June. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahan </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Kleinwort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said that despite the overall drop in factory orders in July, `` there is very little evidence yet that the manufacturing sector is moderating.'' The economy, as measured by the gross national product, grew at a 3.3 percent annual rate in the three months ended in June and at a 3.4 percent pace in the first quarter. In an effort to ease inflationary pressures, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has attempted to dampen economic growth by boosting short-term interest rates since late March.
</TEXT>
