<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices have moved higher in moderate trading, with gasoline prices advancing in pre-Labor Day weekend activity. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, contracts for October delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, rose 5 cents per barrel Tuesday to close at $ 15.27. Other contract months also rose. Refined petroleum products moved higher, with near-term contracts for gasoline leading the way. Contracts for September delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.79 cent to finish at 48.03 cents a gallon. Other contracts also finished higher. Wholesale heating oil for September rose 0.38 cent to 43.14 cents a gallon while other contract months also gained. Analysts said gasoline prices were strong in anticipation of demand during the Labor Day weekend and helped boost crude and other energy prices after a weak opening. `` Gasoline was strong but that's not surprising seeing we're heading into Labor Day, the last hurrah of the summer driving season,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, senior broker and analyst at <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts said expectations that the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly report would show lower gasoline stocks helped keep prices However, traders were expecting buildups in crude and heating oil, which helped slow the rally in crude prices, they said. The API report, released after the close of trading, indicated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil stocks actually dipped by 4.2 million barrels last week while distillate stocks fell by about 3 million barrels. Gasoline stocks rose by 699,000 barrels.
