<HEAD>Two Former Continental Illinois Officials Sentenced to Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two former bank officers sentenced to prison for crimes that contributed to the near-collapse of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> say they are relieved that years of court proceedings are over. Sentenced in a hearing were <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> vice president, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, the head of energy lending at the now-defunct <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Square </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The two pleaded guilty to charges stemming from an alleged scheme that left <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> holding millions of dollars in bad energy loans from <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. Penn Square failed in 1982, and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> nearly collapsed two years later following an unprecedented run on its deposits. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> to 3 -LCB- years in prison, despite <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>'s pleas for probation. <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, who choked back tears as he spoke in his own defense, to a 2-year term. <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, 53, and <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, 38, pleaded guilty June 30 to one criminal charge each for a scheme in which <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> allegedly took kickbacks in exchange for arranging to have <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> buy millions of dollars in risky energy loans from <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. The maximum sentence allowed under their plea bargain was five years. `` I'm going to be able to put a red circle on my calendar which signals the end of this affair,'' <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> told the judge before sentencing. He said he had lived under indictment for more than six years. <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, who held his head and cried as he spoke, said he was sorry for his actions and was concerned about his family. He also had sought a sentence of probation and community service. `` I'm sorry for the people in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` I think of that a lot.'' <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Burck </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, said after the sentencing that `` We're relieved to have it behind us.'' <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said he was convinced the ordeal had harmed <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>'s long-term health He said <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> had to be carried from court when acquitted of charges in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> related to <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, only to find out the next day he had been indicted in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Testifying before his sentencing, <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> said he accepted responsibility for his actions. He asked the judge to sentence him to no more than six months in prison and assign him to work with the poor on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Shadur </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> seemed, at times, `` unwilling to confront the realities'' of what he had done. `` You allowed your conduct as a bank officer ... to be driven impermissibly by your desire for personal benefits,'' the judge told <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> pleaded guilty to misapplication of bank funds and <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> pleaded guilty to a charge that he aided and abetted <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>. The pleas came two months after a trial of the two ended with a deadlocked ury. Prosecutors said <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> had manipulated <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON> and a third man, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> drilling contractor <PERSON> Jere </PERSON> <PERSON> Sturgis </PERSON>, in schemes to save his own failing bank. <PERSON> Sturgis </PERSON> was acquitted of wire fraud charges. Defense attorneys contended <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, which was kept afloat by a $ 4.5 billion government bailout, was saddled with the troublesome energy loans because of an aggressive lending policy. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said his client was in over his head when assigned to handle <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>'s oil and gas leasing loans. He said it was a time of seemingly endless expansion, causing bankers to `` throw caution to the wind.''
