<HEAD>Griffin Gets Resorts Stockholder Approval, But Not Nod From
Regulators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Entertainer <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> has received approval from a majority of <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stockholders to buy the gaming and real estate company, but state gaming regulators have thrown up a roadblock. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s proposed trust agreement _ needed before he can buy the Resorts stock from Class A shareholders and controlling stockholder <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> _ failed to win approval Tuesday from the state <ORGANIZATION> Casino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The trust agreement is necessary in case the commission finds <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> ineligible for a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> gaming license. In that case, the trust would run the company until <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> could appeal the decision or sell off the company's assets. The commission voted 3-2 against the proposed trust agreement, largely because it calls for a trustee to take control of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> rather than just the Resorts stock. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> officials wanted the trust agreement to cover The <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to ensure the firm can take advantage of prior tax losses of Resorts, potentially worth $ 100 million. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s deal to buy Resorts was to expire at midnight Tuesday, but <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Trump </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, said after the commission meeting that he expected <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> to extend the offer for another 30 days. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> was present at Tuesday's hearing, but did not testify. The former talk show host said afterward he had asked the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for clarification on the tax issue, and he still expects the deal to go through. Commissioners <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeitz </PERSON> and <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Waters </PERSON> argued that The <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> did not do enough to satisfy the law concerning the structure of the trust. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> also must obtain approvals from the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Bahamian </LOCATION> government where a Resorts facility is located, said Resorts President I.G. `` Jack'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. The deal also is contingent upon settlement of shareholder litigation now pending in the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and another lawsuit by Showboat Hotel Casino. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who owns Resorts Class B stock _ which has 100 times the voting power of the Class A stock _ will receive $ 135 a share, or about $ 96 million. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> will also receive another $ 63 million to break his management agreement with Resorts, and he will then buy the company's unfinished Taj Mahal casino project for $ 255 million. Holders of the 5.7 million Class A shares will receive $ 36 a share under <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s offer, or a total of $ 205.2 million. On Tuesday, holders of 2.9 million Class A shares _ just slightly over the number needed to approve the proposal _ agreed to accept <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s offer. More than 236,000 voted against the deal, and more than 58,000 abstained.
