<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Ruling Against Bendectin Class-Action Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BENTLEY BOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court panel has ruled in favor of the maker of the drug Bendectin in a class-action suit by some 1,150 plaintiffs who claimed the anti-nausea drug caused birth defects. The attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Merrell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of Bendectin, said the decision by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 6th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upholding a 1985 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision was the most important yet in Bendectin-related litigation, which has been active for years. `` It shows the plaintiffs' lawyers lost fair and square,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodside </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, <PERSON> Merrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON>'s attorney. A federal court jury in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> decided in March 1985 after five weeks of testimony that the drug did not cause birth defects when taken in prescribed doses by pregnant women. The three-judge appeals panel upheld the verdict, as well as Judge <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>'s decision to keep the jury from seeing all plaintiffs who had birth defects. <ORGANIZATION> Woodside </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Merrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> has not asked that plaintiffs be removed in any of the individual Bendectin suits against <ORGANIZATION> Merrell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> in other courts, but was concerned that `` having hundreds of children testify'' may have distracted the jury and attorneys in the class-action case. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesley </PERSON>, one of the attorneys representing more than 800 individual suits in the class action, did not return phone calls Tuesday. Appeals Judge <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> dissented in part Tuesday by saying the judge should have first met with the excluded plaintiffs before denying them their day in court. The appeals court also affirmed <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>'s decision to split the trial into two parts. If the jury had found that the drug caused defects, there would have been subsequent trials to determine any negligence or damages. The court also upheld <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>'s ruling that the district court did not have jurisdiction in 80 of the 1,150 cases. Those 80 cases were dismissed or sent back to state court. An estimated 32 million pregnant women worldwide took Bendectin or its overseas version, Debendox, from 1956 to 1983. <PERSON> Merrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> voluntarily removed it from the market in 1983, although it maintains the drug is safe and does not cause birth defects in children. <PERSON> Merrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> said in a news release that it had won 22 jury verdicts or judgments in Bendectin birth defect suits, and was appealing four trial verdicts won by plaintiffs. <ORGANIZATION> Woodside </ORGANIZATION> said dozens of lawyers across the country were awaiting the appeals court ruling before deciding if they should file similar claims against the company, which is based in suburban Reading. `` It's going to have precedential effect all over the place,'' <ORGANIZATION> Woodside </ORGANIZATION> said. `` This opinion is a very thorough review of all the issues presented to the court of appeals.''
