<HEAD>Judge Bars Eastern Layoffs, Allows Route Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6 of Aug. 30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has 140 fewer flights today, but because of a federal judge's ruling still employs 4,000 workers it wanted to lay off. Eastern is going ahead with previously announced plans to curtail service from 14 cities in the aftermath of an order Tuesday by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> Barrington </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>. The order allowed route cuts but barred the company from making mass layoffs without negotiating with its unions. `` Massive layoffs are not, and shall never be, business as usual,'' <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> wrote in a 50-page opinion. `` The Railway Labor Act requires Eastern to bargain with its unions before taking unilateral action to eliminate 12 percent of its workforce.'' <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> signed a preliminary injunction barring Eastern from `` altering in any way the status quo working condition of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots, machinists and flight attendants. A trial will be scheduled later. Eastern President <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> called the decision `` gravely wrong'' and said the carrier would file an emergency appeal. `` Eastern, like any <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> business, must be allowed to prune money-losing operations,'' Bakes said in a statement released at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters here. `` We must be able to take prudent, although sometimes painful, measures in the best interests of the company and our employees.'' Overall, Eastern is discontinuing 204 flights, mostly in the West and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, with some new flights resulting in a net reduction of 140 Eastern flights. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s opinion did not spell out what should happen to the employees whose jobs were salvaged, even though their duties were not. Union attorneys suggested they could be transferred, and leaders of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s three unions said they wanted to meet with management to discuss ways to cut costs without layoffs. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> 100, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s largest union with 12,000 workers of 32,500 Eastern employees, called the decision an opportunity for <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to belie his reputation as `` the No 1 union-buster.'' `` We're not here as laborers trying to direct the business of the airline. We're trying to protect jobs,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vician </PERSON>, vice-chairman of the pilots' local. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, local president, said the flight attendants still were willing to offer a job-sharing and leave plan _ rejected earlier by management _ to save jobs and money Lawyers for the three unions submitted financial statements, and <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> ordered bonds of $ 25,000 each to indemnify the airline if the decision is reversed. Meanwhile, the airline said: `` Eastern's basic fall schedule remains intact. Travel agents and passengers can continue to book flights with full confidence that the schedule will be as announced.'' <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said the service cuts, which reduce <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s daily flights from 1,225 to 1,085, were financially motivated. Eastern says the route cuts will save $ 50 million monthly in operating costs, and the layoffs would have saved another $ 7 million monthly. Eastern posted a second-quarter net loss of $ 89.8 million, following a $ 64.5 million first-quarter loss and $ 182 million in 1987 losses. Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> has warned it needs cash to k