<HEAD>Senior Bank of Japan Officials Not Considering Rate Hike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senior Bank of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> officials indicated that the central bank has no plans to raise its discount rate despite recent interest-rate hikes in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. At a briefing Wednesday for Japanese reporters, bank officials said it is part of the central bank's contribution to international policy coordination not to push up the key interest rate. The officials did not elaborate. The news sent the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar up sharply against the Japanese yen in foreign-exchange trading. Other central bank officials were quoted as saying that the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> might have to intervene to stop the yen's decline. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Bank of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> officials made the remarks after the dollar rose above 136 yen in European trading on the earlier reports that the Japanese central bank would not raise rates. Last week, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> raised its discount rate a half point and several European banks quickly followed. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> had made a similar move a few weeks earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> quoted some <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> officials as saying the yen-dollar rates have reached a level that should be watched very carefully and that action might be warranted if new movements in the currencies occur. The remarks appeared to indicate that the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> may intervene to brake the dollar's rise if the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency continues to advance. The central bank does n't want to see the yen slide further against the dollar because of concern about higher domestic inflation. The yen's sharp appreciation since late 1985 has helped to hold down domestic prices. But accelerated growth in money supply amid the present robust economic expansion and the yen's recent downturn have spawned worries about inflation. According to <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> officials said they would consider not only the yen's levels against the dollar but the pace of its decline and the strength of yen selling, in deciding whether or not to intervene against the dollar's rise. The senior <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> officials, who indicated that no rate hike is in the works, described the recent key rate increases by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and European central banks as aimed at fighting inflation. They said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> rate increases `` honor the spirit'' of policy coordination by the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> major industrial countries, since it advocates stemming inflation in order to sustain world economic growth. The Group of Seven countries are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Some foreign-exchange and money-market participants said Japanese monetary authorities have refrained from raising the discount rate because such a move would make Japanese funds more expensive overseas and may prove counterproductive in keeping the global economy on an expansionary track. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is a launching pad of investment funds for the world. The -LRB- <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> -RRB- and other industrialized countries would do whatever they could to keep <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> from raising interest rates further,'' said an official at <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>.
