<SECOND>BC-EEC-Anti-Dumping,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Slaps Antidumping Duties On Korean, Japanese VCR Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday slapped provisional antidumping duties on exports of video cassette recorders from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> after complaints by domestic manufacturers. The duties follow a surge in VCR exports to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> since 1985, primarily from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> who tripled its VCR exports to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in a year's time, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said. The duties affect three South Korean companies that account for all of that country's VCR exports, including <ORGANIZATION> Daewoo </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Goldstar </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Samsung </ORGANIZATION>. The Japanese companies affected are <ORGANIZATION> Funai </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION>. The commission said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s VCR exports into <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> surged from 75,000 in 1985, to 425,000 in 1986 and 1.22 million last year. Imports from the two Japanese companies more than doubled to 991,000 units in 1986, from 466,000 in 1985. In the first eight months of 1987, 762,000 <ORGANIZATION> Funai </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> VCRs entered the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, the commission said. The duties levied include 29.2 percent for <ORGANIZATION> Daewoo </ORGANIZATION>; 26.4 percent for <ORGANIZATION> Goldstar </ORGANIZATION>; 25.2 percent for <ORGANIZATION> Samsung </ORGANIZATION>; and 18 percent on <ORGANIZATION> Funai </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> VCRs. The level of the duties was fixed after a commission inquiry into the sharp rise of VCR imports. The Commission began its probe in September 1987 on a complaint by an <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> industry association representing producers of consumer electronics. The group complained that VCR imports from the three South Korean and two Japanese firms surged because of their artificially low prices. The group's members include <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> BV </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Grundig </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Telefunken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fernsehen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> und </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rundfunk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GMBH </ORGANIZATION>, both of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ferguson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> The Commission said it found that the South Korean and Japanese companies sold VCRs in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> at dumping prices, or at prices considered unfairly low. As a result, their combined share of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s VCR market rose to 30 percent last year from 8.6 percent in 1985. Since 1985, VCR purchases in the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> rose to 7 million from 5.8 million European Currency Units -LRB- or the equivalent of $ 7.7 from $ 6.38 million -RRB-, the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said. It concluded the market share gains of the South Korean and Japanese exporters were made at the expense of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s VCR industry and that their dumping prices lowered the sales and profit margins of their <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> competitors.
