<HEAD>Government Urges More Cautious Approach To Price Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top Chinese government officials have decided against rapid decontrol of state-set prices, a key element in the nation's economic reforms, in an apparent move to ease unhappiness with spiraling inflation. The cautious approach toward price reform disclosed Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Cabinet, differed from a more aggressive outline adopted by the Communist Party Politburo in mid-August, and highlighted the growing debate within the leadership over how fast <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> should proceed with its reforms. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s stand was widely reported in the official media Wednesday, with the national evening news devoting five minutes to explaining the decisions made. The council agreed not to initiate further price increases for the remainder of this year and decided there will be no radical reforms in the price system next year. The nation will continue to restrain construction projects and other capital investments that have pushed industrial growth to unsustainable levels and will further control credit and the issuance of currency to cool off the overheated economy, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said. It also said a five-year plan of price and wage reform outlined by the Politburo in mid-August is still tentative and subject to revision. The Politburo plan called for removal of price controls on most commodities in favor of market regulation. The plan, while also stressing the need to control a near-runaway inflation rate, said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economy `` is full of vitality and is developing vigorously. The time is favorable to the price and wage reforms.'' The 17-member Politburo, the main decision-making body of the party, is led by General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, the leading advocate of rapid market-oriented reform. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, is headed by Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>, who is thought to be more cautious toward change and more concerned about the effects of reform on economic and social stability. There is consensus in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> about the pressing need for price reform, primarily the removal of state controls so that the value of goods can be determined by market forces. Artificially low state-set prices for many products have led to chronic shortages, corruption, influence peddling and a thriving black market. Profiteers commonly buy up low-priced raw materials and items from state factories and resell them for far higher prices to producers and consumers. Decontrol of prices of some basic goods and foods in the past year, coupled with the inability of producers to meet rising consumer demand, have pushed inflation to levels never before acknowledged in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s communist system. In June prices were 19 percent higher than a year earlier.
</TEXT>
