<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv01   08-31 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 01,0526</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Sept. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>Demographics Suggest Housing Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For at least one industry, housing _ including building, sales and rentals _ the script was written in the 1950s and 1960s and will be played out in the 1990s. The plot is a demographic one: A two-decade bulge of Americans of homebuying age will have passed through the economy, leaving a still large but substantially smaller demand for lower-priced starter homes. Among the characters affected will be developers, lenders, builders, trades people, brokers, materials suppliers and investors. `` They have no choice but to accept that notion and accommodate themselves to the reality,'' says <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Lomas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, and publisher of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION>, a subscription newsletter. The latest analysis by the newsletter, whose surveys and studies are widely accepted in the housing industry, offers these demographic-based projections: _ Annual household formations gradually will fall to less than two-thirds of the 1984-1987 average _ Private housing starts will average no more than 1.4 million a year for most of the decade of the 1990s, compared with 2 million in 1977 and more than 1.7 million in the years 1983-1985 _ New housing will shift inexorably toward higher price ranges, reflecting the greater affluence and grander lifestyles of older buyers _ Traditional rental apartments aimed at younger tenants will be in less demand Says <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON>: `` Landlords will need to find innovative products to attract households in higher age brackets.'' _ Housing targeted for older Americans _ those retired or planning retirement _ will be find a growing market <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON> butresses his conclusions with immutable demographic evidence: In 1975, for example, nearly 40 million Americans were in their 20s, the primary market bracket for apartments and starter homes, while only 23 million were in the `` move-up'' category of 35 years to 44 years. By the end of the century the numbers will almost flipflop, with more than 43 million individuals in the age 35 to 44 bracket, while those in their 20s will have contracted to 34 million. These numbers portend a development that might also have a serious impact on those who currently own homes and are relying on the equity in them to finance their retirements. <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON> describes the potential phenomenon in this way: `` As <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> ages, as the middle-years cohort climbs the ladder from first moveup and thence to second, third and fourth, the lower rungs will be holding fewer and fewer potential buyers. `` The homes being left behind will be offered to a dwindling list of prospects. `` Thus, in overall terms, the existing-home market will gradually evolve into a buyers' market, beginning in the lower regions of the price spectrum.'' The situation <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON> describes does n't dictate lower prices, nor does it mean that prices can not increase. But it strongly suggests that the sharp price increases of the 1970s and 1980s will be, by the year 2000, a thing of the past.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday Sept. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
