Commission probe.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal probe into accounting procedures at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, involving a possible attempt to avoid paying $ 50 million in taxes, may involve other companies and individuals, the government says. Court documents made public Tuesday showed the investigation now focuses on <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>, its parent, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and the Big Eight accounting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, who confirmed the investigation, said the probe is continuing and may involve others. Meanwhile, the state <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said today it has upgraded its own investigation of tax and accounting practices at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> and specifically wants to know whether the utility attempted to hide vital financial information from <ORGANIZATION> PSC </ORGANIZATION> scrutiny. <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> refused to elaborate beyond what was in the court papers because a grand jury is still hearing details. He said the investigation involves possible criminal wrongdoing, including violations of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Tax Code. A statement issued by <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> from the company's <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> headquarters denied any wrongdoing. But <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>, speaking for the electric utility and <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said he was shocked by the allegations and vowed to `` get to the bottom of this matter.'' The papers raised the question of whether the companies and their accountants sought to hide about $ 61 million in spare parts to avoid paying $ 50 million in federal taxes, interest and penalties. Key elements in that question are whether parts are classified as emergency spares or for maintainence and when they become expenses to the company. The papers also raised the question of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>'s accounting for the sale of 5 percent of the Vogtle nuclear power plant to the <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> In the documents, officials say the deal was treated as a sale of 5 percent of the $ 8.87 billion plant for book value purposes, but as 1.35 percent for tax purposes, saving the company between $ 10 million and $ 12 million. The papers include excerpts of taped conversations in which <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s tax chief agrees with an informant that the company misled the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> over the tax accounting of the spare parts, but adds, `` Do n't ever say that.'' The investigation, dating to 1982, is based largely on information contained in taped conversations between utility and <LOCATION> Andersen </LOCATION> officials and the informant, <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> employee <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilman </PERSON>, who is getting paid for his participation and been exempted from prosecution, the court papers show. The papers also include affidavits requesting search warrants at the downtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> headquarters of <ORGAN