<HEAD>Winery Owners Win Legal Battle With Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has dismissed an attempt by the younger brother of <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> to gain one-third ownership of the world's largest winery. However, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON> ruled Tuesday that <ORGANIZATION> E </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; J Gallo Winery's trademark infringement suit against <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> will proceed to trial on Nov. 15. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> had charged that use of <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>'s last name on a brand of cheese he produced violated their trademark <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> countersued, contending that his older brothers comingled assets from their parents' estate to begin the <LOCATION> Modesto </LOCATION>, Calif.-based Gallo Winery in 1933. Price said he found no legal basis for <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>'s contention. The judge said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>'s allegation that <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> concealed part of the parents' estate `` clearly fails.'' Price said evidence presented to the court of the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> family making wine before prohibition is `` mostly the stuff that family anecdotes are made of.'' `` The court can only conclude that <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON>'s administration was appropriate and that all of the assets of the estate were reported and administered,'' the judge said. `` It was always our belief that once the true facts were known, this ludicrous and false claim would be thrown out of court,'' Gallo Winery spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said. Attorney <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said he will continue trying to let <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> use his own name on his own products. `` I continue to believe <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> is entitled to use his own name in his own business,'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said. `` We intend to move forward with that phase of the case at the appropriate time.'' Price said several issues must be resolved in the trademark trial. They include a contention by <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> that the winery made false statements in applying for a trademark to the name <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, which means rooster in Italian. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> contended that their father began using the trademark in 1909. `` The court can not say that a fraud was practiced upon the trademark officials by the winery during the registration process,'' Price said. `` It is simply the position of the court that the record does not establish that the statements made to secure the trademark, as a matter of law, bar the winery from the relief it seeks. `` That issue remains for trial,'' he said.
