<FIRST>r f BC-ColaSentencing     08-31 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cola Sentencing,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Bottling Company to `Corporate Imprisonment'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge said his sentence of `` corporate imprisonment'' for a soft-drink bottling company convicted of price fixing was unprecedented, but was justified for a company that `` did not have a conscience.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> suspended the sentence and placed <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> on probation Tuesday, saying any violation of probation would result in the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Marshal being sent to `` padlock every facility Allegheny owns.'' <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> also imposed the maximum fine of $ 1 million, suspending $ 50,000 and ordering four top corporate officers to perform as much as two years of full-time, unpaid community service. `` The corporation can not come in here, profit to the tune of $ 10 million and walk away with a $ 1 million fine,'' <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said. `` I can not imagine any company being more tied up with illegal activity.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, a lawyer for <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION>, said he would appeal the sentence, adding that he could find no precedent of corporate imprisonment. <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> also ordered that <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> not sell any of its assets without the court's permission. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said <PERSON> Allegheny </PERSON>'s parent company, <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION>, had planned to sell some of <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION>'s assets this week and that the sentence could result in a `` financial fiasco.'' <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said he would consider the transactions in private but would not allow the company to be left with no one to fullfill the terms of probation. The government said <PERSON> Allegheny </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> bottling franchise, and its arch rival, <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottlng </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, ended years of cola wars in 1982 by secretly rigging wholesale prices in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. Prosecutors said a number of executives, including <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> multimillionaire <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON>, who founded <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION>, orchestrated the conspiracy. <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> later sold the company, which is now owned by <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said virtually every executive at <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> was in on the scheme. `` Where was there a beacon of some sanity?'' <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> asked. `` Was there any? Did anyone care? Why did n't anyone care?'' `` Some 200 years ago, the Lord Chancellor of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> said, ` You can not expect a corporation to have a conscience when it has no soul to be damned and no body to be kicked ... Obviously, <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> did not have a conscience ...'' <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> said he could find no similar case of corporate imprisonment to justify his sentence, but added, `` stone walls do not a prison make.'' He said the sentence would discourage other potential price fixers from making illegal agreements with competitors. <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>, former president of <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coca-Cola </LOCATION>, were found guilty by a federal jury in May of price fixing. Last week, <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> received three-year prison terms, with all but six months suspended, and were fined $ 100,000 each.
