<FIRST>r f AM-BellSouth-Gateway     08-31 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BellSouth-Gateway,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>BellSouth Becomes First Bell Company to Offer Information Gateway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TranstexT in 2nd graf is CQ</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday unveiled an electronic gateway that will allow computer users to reach several information services with a single local phone call. <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION>, the first <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> company to offer such a service, said its TranstexT Universal Gateway is available in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> calling area. After the initial introduction there, <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> plans to make the gateway available in other cities in its nine-state region. `` We believe information services are an important'' segment of the telecommunications industry `` and it's important for our business to be involved,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> vice president for information services. But <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>, alluding to several failed attempts by companies to launch videotex services, said <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> will proceed slowly and `` we're going to be listening a lot'' to see how information service providers and users respond to the gateway. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, in modifying the consent decree that stripped <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of its local <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> operating companies, ruled last year that <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies could establish gateways to transmit electronic information supplied by others. He continued to bar them, however, from originating any of the information themselves. Without a gateway, computer users with a modem must pre-subscribe to the various information services that are available and dial into each one separately. They also are billed by each separately. Using the <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> gateway, a computer user needs only to subscribe to it and can then dial one phone number to reach multiple information services. Subscribers will be billed by <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Networks </ORGANIZATION>, an unregulated subsidiary, for use of the gateway and for the information services they used. Currently, eight services are available through the gateway and 10 more are scheduled to be added soon, the company said. The services that are already on line offer information about an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> theater company, local and national news, the stock market and travel, among other things. One service sponsored by an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> hospital provides health and fitness information and plans soon to offer an on-line heart test. Another service allows callers to `` chat'' electronically with one another. <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> said the company hoped to sign up 300 customers during the initial offering and slowly grow to 1,000 in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> before offering the service in other areas. Gateway charges are $ 1.50 per hour from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. and $ 3 per hour during the other 12 hours of the day. Users would be charged an additional fee depending on how much information they access _ typically about 60 cents during the day and 40 cents at night, <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> said. Customers also must pay for the cost of access to any of the information services on the gateway. A couple of the services charge nothing, but the cost of others range up to $ 50 an hour. Computer users may pay more for some services obtained through the gateway than if they dialed into the service directly. But, depending on the time of day, some services may be cheaper through the gateway. For example, Travel Plus, which is part of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Videotex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Delphi </ORGANIZATION> service, charges $ 7.80 an hour on the gateway, day or night. But when a caller dials into <ORGANIZATION> Delphi </ORGANIZATION> and calls up Travel Plus, it costs $ 7.40 per hour during the evening but $ 17.40 during the day. The daytime rate reflects the higher cost of data lines needed for computer transmissions, said <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, marketing director of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Videotex </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
