<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market closed with some spotty losses today after an early advance faded. Stocks headed higher at the opening as the dollar climbed in foreign exchange on reports suggesting that Japanese officials planned no immediate move to increase interest rates. That, in turn, prompted slightly higher prices, and hence lower interest rates, for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government securities in the credit markets. Analysts also said hopes were increasing on Wall Street that Friday's report on the employment situation for August would show a moderation in job growth, which would presumably ease pressure for credit-tightening by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. With all those positives, however, the pace of trading remained relatively light as the long Labor Day weekend approached. Brokers said the market was still suffering from the apathy and caution that has predominated in recent sessions.
