<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Move Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar staged a strong advance Wednesday, bolstered by a sharp decline in the Japanese yen. Gold prices also moved higher. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 430.30 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $ 428.35 late Tuesday. The dollar's gains came at the expense of the yen, which weakened anew in overseas trading after <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> officials hinted they would not raise their discount rate despite recent interest rate hikes in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` The yen went through the floor,'' said one dealer in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The dollar's gains against the yen encouraged it to climb against other currencies, dealers said. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar jumped 1.59 yen to close at 136.52 yen. Earlier in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to finish at 136.50 yen. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.58 yen to close at 134.97 yen. The yen began weakening late Tuesday on rumors that the Japanese government plans to impose a tax on certain stock-trading profits. `` Stories are going around left and right about what the Japanese may or may not do,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, a senior trader at <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In domestic dealings, traders noted that the dollar closed off its session highs. `` There was some profit-taking and some month-end squaring'' of positions, noted <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON>, chief dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office. `` The dollar reached the stage where -LRB- <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> said it would do anything to defend the mark,'' he said, prompting traders to sell dollars. The central banks did not intervene to halt the dollar's rise. But dealers in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> said they fear the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> will enter the market if the dollar tops the 1.8800 level against the mark. The dollar gained against the British pound. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> it cost $ 1.6830 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.6910 late Tuesday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> it cost $ 1.6860 to buy one pound, less expensive than Tuesday's $ 1.6875. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Tuesday, included: 1.8765 West German marks, up from 1.8664; 1.5848 Swiss francs, up from 1.5765; 6.3740 French francs, up from 6.3385; 1,394.50 Italian lire, up from 1,386.00, and 1.2392 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2362. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Tuesday, included: 1.8780 West German marks, up from 1.8678; 1.5828 Swiss francs, up from 1.5760; 6.3755 French francs, up from 6.3385; 2.1230 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1080; 1,395.75 Italian lire, up from 1,387.50, and 1.2395 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2386. Gold bullion for current delivery rose to $ 431.30 a troy ounce on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, from $ 428.80 at Tuesday's close. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 429.50 a troy ounce, compared with late Tuesday's $ 428.10. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 429.50 an ounce, up from $ 428.50 late Tuesday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 2.60 per ounce to close at a bid $ 429.96. Silver bullion for current delivery rose to $ 6.556 a troy ounce on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> from $ 6.490 on Tuesday. Silver bullion prices fell slightly in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.52 a troy ounce, compared with Tuesday's $ 6.55.
