<FIRST>u f AM-DroughtInsurance Bjt   08-31 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Insurance, Bjt,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deadline Arrives For Rainfall Under Disputed Drought Insurance
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, summer ended at midnight Wednesday, the cutoff for measuring rainfall under the insurer's controversial drought coverage plan that has farmers suing, insurance departments angry and <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> officials struggling for damage control A spokeswoman at the <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, N.J.-based company, who spoke on condition that she not be identified by name, said several weeks would be needed to determine the amount of <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION>'s liability. The insurer hopes to pay all claims by early October, she said. Reports from 1,100 U.S. Weather Measuring Stations will filter in to <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION>'s computer. Some of the stations are remote, making collection of the data more difficult, she said. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> officials have said that recent rainfall after dry weeks in June and July may have relieved it having to pay roughly half the $ 40 million in coverage granted. `` It's certainly been raining, and it's substantially reduced our exposure,'' said the spokeswoman. The policies, granted to 1,160 farmers, promise payments if rainfall is less than half _ or less than 70 percent, depending on the policy _ of an area's average rainfall from June 1 to Aug. 31. A check Wednesday with weather officials in Farm Belt states showed a range of roughly calculated rainfall levels for the eriod, though it is difficult to estimate what the effect might be on <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION>'s liability. In <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, about 15 percent of the state had less than half normal rainfall; 55 percent to 60 percent received less than the 70 percent threshhold. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> reported that less than 10 percent of the state fell below the halfway mark and just under half had less than 70 percent of the average. Rainfall in more than two-thirds of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> dipped below 70 percent of the average, and one-fifth was below 50 percent. In <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, more than half the state received less than 50 percent of normal rainfall from April 1 to Aug. 1, and nearly all of it dipped below 70 percent. Twenty-two counties in the southeast quarter of <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> alone received less than 70 percent of normal rain since January. Figures since June were not available. Weather officials in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, said rainfall was about 22 percent shy of normal for the June 1-Aug. 31 period, and that conditions in the rest of the state appeared similar The Chubb policy became embroiled in controversy when the company was flooded with applications that exceeded the amount of coverage it had authorized. Agents offered an estimated $ 400 million in insurance compared to the $ 30 million limit, which <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> later increased to $ 40 million. About 8,700 farmers applied. Angered over the disparity, farmers sued <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> and the cases were consolidated in a class-action suit in federal court in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. Insurance regulators in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> have scheduled hearings on the issue. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> offered to return double the premiums paid by farmers who were denied a policy, and has sent about 6,000 checks totaling $ 20 million, the spokeswoman said. Midnight Wednesday was also the deadline for farmers to have letters postmarked asking for the doubled refunds. Lawyers for farmers in the <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> case said an agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> lawyers was filed promising that the double payments could be requested without forfeiting the right to sue. The Chubb spokeswoman said the promise was part of the company's original refund offer She also said the deadline would not be extended. She said most of the applying farmers had been contacted by telephone about the potential refund, but an unidentified numbers of others could not be reached and had been written. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> has reacted to the image crisis created by the controversey not just with the refunds but with full-page newspaper ads, toll-free numbers and a special task force staffed by 125 people. The volume of phone calls Wednesday was not heavier than usual, the company said.
</TEXT>
