<HEAD>Lawsuit Claims $30 Million In Post-Crash Losses At Options
Exchange</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf with 3 new grafs to define index options and
INSERT dropped word `of' in 6th graf; picks up 7th graf pvs: The
exchange ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and some of its traders overcharged more than 1,000 investors who lost at least $ 40 million the day after the stock market collapsed, a lawyer charged Wednesday after filing a lawsuit. The <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> and floor traders responsible for making markets in certain options on the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 100 stock index violated federal law and the exchange's own rules by charging inflated prices for options contracts last Oct. 20, attorney <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Beigel </PERSON> alleged in a class-action lawsuit. `` The investors were gouged by virtue of being charged excessive prices,'' <PERSON> Beigel </PERSON>, a partner in the Chicago-based law firm <ORGANIZATION> Beigel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON>, said in a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office. `` The market makers, with the assistance of the <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION>, deliberately charged investors very excessive prices, which made it difficult for the investors to make money because there was not a legitimate market.'' <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> officials were aware of the lawsuit, which consolidates three previous class-action lawsuits, but would not comment on it, said spokesman <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Moulds </PERSON>. An option is a contract giving the holder the right to buy or sell a commodity or financial instrument for a specific price at a future date. In the case of <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 100 index options, the item being traded is the value of the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 100 index, which measures the performance of 100 stocks. The price or premium of an index option depends on a number of variables, including the time until the expiration of the option and the volatility of the underlying index. The <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION>, the world's leading options exchange, has said the doubling and tripling of index options prices on Oct. 20 were understandable in light of the market's unprecedented volatility that day. The exchange also facilitated the collection of $ 1.2 million earmarked as refunds for investors who paid extremely high prices for <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 100 index options contracts on Oct. 20. The money was collected from traders and distributed to brokerage firms. But <PERSON> Beigel </PERSON> said the refunds amounted to, at most, 20 percent of the total lost by some investors. The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, combines and broadens the claims of the three previous lawsuits. It seeks an amount equal to the money invested less any returns or refunds, plus an unspecified amount for lost use of the money and interest. It names as plaintiffs all people who purchased OEX - or OEZ-series index options on Oct. 20 at the <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION>, except those who acted as market makers for such transactions The lawsuit names as defendants the <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clearing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a separate firm that processes trades made at the exchange; and all <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> floor traders who were designated as market makers for the OEX and OEZ series of <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 100 index options on Oct. 20. Trading losses in index options on Oct. 19 and 20 have been estimated at several hundred million dollars nationwide. Index options were among the largest sources of investor complaints in the weeks after the 508-point drop in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average on Oct. 19. Index options, which account for more than half the trading volume at the <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION>, are hedging tools that investors use to protect themselves against losses in the stock market.
