<HEAD>Last Defendant In TRW Case Pleads Guilty To Mail Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former manager for <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> pleaded guilty Wednesday to mail fraud, completing the government's procurement fraud criminal case against the defense contractor, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Broome </PERSON>, 64, of <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, former product line manager of <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION>'s compresser components division, pleaded guilty in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to participating in a scheme to defraud the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said. As part of a plea bargain, the government agreed to dismiss five remaining counts and recommend probation in line with terms given to two other defendants already sentenced, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stickan </PERSON> said. Two more co-defendants are awaiting sentencing. All five co-defendants pleaded guilty. Broome will be sentenced after a report is filed with the court, <PERSON> Stickan </PERSON> said. No date for sentencing was set. The maxiumum penalty is a five years in prison and a $ 1,000 fine. The mail fraud charge involves the falsification of labor expenses in the manufacture of the TF-39 fan blade used in the C-5A military cargo plane, <PERSON> Stickan </PERSON> said. Last Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> paid a $ 3 million penalty after pleading guilty in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to three counts of conspiring to overcharge the federal government for military aircraft and M-1 tank parts. <PERSON> Willliam </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> vice president and assistant secretary, had waived the company's right to a trial and entered a guilty plea for the company before Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> said the company also paid a separate $ 3 million to increase to $ 11.8 million the amount paid toward restitution to the government to settle a pending civil lawsuit. The total amount of the required restitution will be determined in the suit. The company had estimated it overcharged the government between $ 3 million and $ 11 million, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> said. He said the compressor components division was sold in 1986 as part of a restructuring plan.
