<HEAD>Bellcore: Video Wall Next Step In Teleconferencing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Businesses could unite workers at various locations in a telephone conference and create the illusion they are in the same room with a `` video wall,'' <ORGANIZATION> Bellcore </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday in unveiling a prototype. <ORGANIZATION> Bellcore </ORGANIZATION>, a research concern formed after the breakup of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the video wall uses `` image merging'' techniques that bring together images generated by multiple cameras. A final single image can be the product of transmissions from several locations, said co-inventor <PERSON> Lanny </PERSON> <PERSON> Smoot </PERSON>. `` The wall is 8 feet wide for a panoramic view and people appear to be lifelike,'' he said. `` It's as if you were looking through a wall into an adjacent room.'' <PERSON> Smoot </PERSON> said research has shown that workers who may share common concerns or goals do not work together as well if they are in separate buildings or even on different floors in the same building. The video wall could encourage people to work more closely together, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Bellcore </ORGANIZATION>, which has headquarters in <LOCATION> Livingston </LOCATION>, developed the wall at its research center in <LOCATION> Morris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION>. The research and engineering consortium serves the telephone companies of the seven regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> holding companies. <PERSON> Smoot </PERSON> said it will be the companies' decision to market the video wall as a service. <ORGANIZATION> Bellcore </ORGANIZATION> has applied for a patent involving the video merging technique, he said.
