<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Hit 12-Year Low On Threat To International Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Cocoa futures prices tumbled to a 12-year low Wednesday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after an official of the world's top cocoa-producing country said an international price-support agreement was dying. On other markets, pork futures fell sharply; crop futures gained; precious metals were higher; energy futures were lower; and stock-index futures retreated. The shaky price-support agreement of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> sustained another blow Wednesday when <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanon </PERSON>, agriculture minister of the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, told representatives of other producer nations he did not believe the <ORGANIZATION> ICCO </ORGANIZATION> would survive, analysts said. The <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, which produced 29 percent of the world's cocoa last year, has been withholding its cocoa beans from the market in hopes of selling them for higher prices. The <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> also owes about $ 48 million in cocoa levy fees to the <ORGANIZATION> ICCO </ORGANIZATION> to support its operations. <PERSON> Bra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanon </PERSON>'s remarks Wednesday to a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Togo </LOCATION>, had a profound impact on the cocoa market, which had been looking forward to the <ORGANIZATION> ICCO </ORGANIZATION>'s scheduled two-week meeting beginning Sept. 5 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. At that meeting, consumer and producer nations are to begin negotiations toward a new international cocoa price-support agreement. `` A lot of people who may have believed the price of cocoa might rally because of the upcoming meeting were very demoralized,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>, cocoa market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Because of the reluctance of the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and other producers to pay levies, `` the <ORGANIZATION> ICCO </ORGANIZATION> is facing very, very severe financial problems,'' he said. `` How are they going to enforce economic provisions to support prices if they do n't have the cash to keep going?'' In addition to those factors, a glut of cocoa is expected in the upcoming marketing year, which begins Oct. 1. Cocoa settled $ 44 to $ 60 lower with the contract for delivery in September at $ 1,220 per metric ton. Frozen pork-belly futures plunged the permitted 2-cents-a-pound limit on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in a third day of sharp declines in the pork complex. Hog slaughters are increasing on a seasonal basis, and the movement of hogs to market is being accelerated by the earlier-than-normal maturation of corn and soybean crops, analysts said. `` I have a feeling that producers are getting their pens cleaned up and getting ready to turn their attention to the harvest here pretty quick,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Durchholz </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Agri-Visor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, Ill. Most cattle futures moved lower on signs of slackening demand for beef, he said. Live cattle were unchanged to .63 cent lower with October at 71.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .10 cent higher with September at 81.70 cents a pound; hogs were .48 cent to .95 cent lower with October at 38.55 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.42 cents to 2 cents lower with February at 48.90 cents a pound. Grain and soybean futures finished higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> on indications that a long-awaited increase in foreign demand was beginning to surface, analysts said. Prices had opened lower and made little movement until midday, following strong indications that <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> had purchased 300,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> purchased 250,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices while <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> reportedly bought 50,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybeans. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds. Wheat settled 1 cent to 2 cents higher with September at $ 3.97 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 4 cents to 6 -RCB- cents higher with September at $ 2.83 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2 cents higher with September at $ 2.56 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 7 -LCB- cents to 14 cents higher with September at $ 8.54 -LCB- a bushel. Platinum led the precious-metals complex higher in a bounce inspired by technical factors, analysts said. Platinum on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> settled $ 7.80 to $ 8.10 higher with October at $ 533.90 a troy ounce. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold was $ 2.20 to $ 2.50 higher with October at $ 434.10 a troy ounce; silver was 4.5 cents to 6.6 cents higher with September at $ 6.556 a troy ounce Energy futures settled lower on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 9 cents to 28 cents lower with October at $ 15.18 a barrel; heating oil was .19 cent to .61 cent lower with September at 42.95 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .35 cent to 1.49 cents lower with September at 46.54 cents a gallon. Stock-index futures retreated on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for September delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled 1.10 points lower at 261.60.
