<HEAD>Honeywell To Sell Four Units Serving Military Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it plans to sell four units in its Space and <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> business, which serve military markets. The units are its Electro-Optics Division in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>.; Training and <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Covina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> and Production Division in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and Signal Analysis Center in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> said in a prepared statement. `` Our decision to sell these operations reflects <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s resolve to continue focusing on core businesses where we have a competitive advantage to assure that we can achieve our goals,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Renier </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> president and chief executive officer `` The units we intend to sell are good businesses which happen to fall outside the company's strategic focus,'' <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said. In the space and aviation business, <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> is focusing on three strategic core businesses in the commercial aviation, military avionics and space markets, <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said. `` This decision will allow us to concentrate on areas where we have significant market shares and will reduce our exposure in military markets where our competitive advantage is n't as strong,'' he said. In addition, <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> indicated proceeds from the sale of the four units could be applied to the reduction of debt, investment in the company's controls businesses, or the repurchase of stock. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> said approximately 3,500 employees are employed at the four units being sold. The divisions' combined sales were about $ 430 million in 1987, or about 6 percent of the company's total sales of $ 6.7 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s space and aviation business sales totaled $ 1.9 billion in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>, an international control company that provides products, systems and services for the home and building, industrial, space and aviation, and defense and marine markets, has 79,000 employees worldwide.
