<FIRST>u f AM-WPPSSSettlement     08-31 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WPPSS Settlement,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement Reached Between WPPSS, Bondholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> has settled its part of a securities fraud lawsuit brought by bondholders after the system defaulted on $ 2.25 billion in bonds sold to finance two nuclear power plants, attorneys announced Wednesday. Plaintiff bondholders would drop claims against <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> in return for access to power plant accounts containing millions of dollars. Plaintiffs' attorneys also said the deal would gain them the cooperation of <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> employees, who will be leading witnesses in the trial set to start Sept. 7 in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. Remaining defendants include 20 public utilities in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and one in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, three engineering firms and a firm that had provided <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> with financial advice. Attorneys reached the settlement, which had been proposed by the plaintiffs, late Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> Executive Board was expected to approve the agreement at a special meeting Friday in <LOCATION> Richland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Halvorson </PERSON>, board chairman. `` It's a very favorable settlement for the supply system,'' he said. The settlement also needs approval from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, who is presiding over the WPPSS default case. Under the tentative settlement, the plaintiff bondholders agreed to dismiss all claims against <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> based on securities fraud, misrepresentation and violation of state law. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> in turn agreed it had an obligation to pay the face value and interest on the bonds _ which would come to about $ 3 billion _ even though it paid no money in the settlement. The agreement also noted that because of limited assets pledged to secure the bonds, there was `` no expectation'' the money would ever be paid. However, the agreement did give bondholders unconditional access to an account for the terminated plants, Nos. 4 and 5, which has been under control of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, the trustee for plaintiff bondholders, since 1983. The account now has about $ 75 million in it and has withdrawn a total of about $ 90 million, mostly for attorneys' fees. Other additional funds the bondholders might realize from the settlement could come from a pending lawsuit seeking to wrest from two other <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> projects funds that were spent when those plants were `` twinned'' with the terminated projects. That could amount to tens of millions of dollars, but a determination is years away. `` Since you ca n't get blood out of a turnip, why not get all the other benefits you can,'' said <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, who represents class action plaintiffs in the giant lawsuit. The abrupt pullout of <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> from the litigation caught other defendants by surprise, and one said defendants were considering seeking a trial delay. `` We're surprised they -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- did n't stay and defend their actions ...,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Shigley </PERSON>, administrator for the <ORGANIZATION> Snohomish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's not clear that we need more time -LRB- to prepare for trial -RRB-. There is a good chance we will be able to pull it together.'' In addition to access to funds, the settlement will allow plaintiffs to talk with supply system employees before they are put on the stand, according to <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>, a plaintiffs' lawyer, Because of rules in a civil lawsuit, there were questions on whether the <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> employees even would have to testify. Bondholders had sued the supply system, 88 utilities, bond underwriters, various directors and managers, engineering firms and advisors after <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> defaulted on $ 2.25 billion worth of bonds to build the two never-completed nuclear power plants. Many defendants, including bond underwriters and more than 60 utilities, have reached settlements totaling $ 331 million over the past year.
</TEXT>
